ZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"77f7e140-f822-4d31-b9c1-413b964f0dde\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.548Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"77f7e140-f822-4d31-b9c1-413b964f0dde\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01NVeXzEwmNj9jpNxAhuPBRp\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# E2E Tests\\n     2→\\n     3→End-to-end tests for the `entire` CLI against real agents (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, OpenCode, Cursor, Copilot CLI).\\n     4→\\n     5→## Commands\\n     6→\\n     7→```bash\\n     8→mise run test:e2e [filter]                          # run filtered (or omit filter for all agents)\\n     9→mise run test:e2e --agent claude-code [filter]       # Claude Code only\\n    10→mise run test:e2e --agent gemini-cli [filter]        # Gemini CLI only\\n    11→mise run test:e2e --agent opencode [filter]          # OpenCode only\\n    12→mise run test:e2e --agent copilot-cli [filter]       # Copilot CLI only\\n    13→mise run test:e2e --agent cursor-cli [filter]        # Cursor only\\n    14→go build ./...                                      # compile check (no agent CLI needed)\\n    15→```\\n    16→\\n    17→**Do NOT run E2E tests proactively.** They make real API calls that consume tokens and cost money. Only run when explicitly asked.\\n    18→\\n    19→## Structure\\n    20→\\n    21→```\\n    22→e2e/\\n    23→├── agents/       # Agent abstraction (Agent interface, tmux sessions, concurrency gates)\\n    24→├── bootstrap/    # CI pre-test setup (auth config, warmup)\\n    25→├── entire/       # `entire` CLI wrapper (enable, rewind, etc.)\\n    26→├── exploratory/  # Experimental tests, not run by CI\\n    27→├── tests/        # Blessed test files (run by CI)\\n    28→└── testutil/     # Repo setup, assertions, artifact capture\\n    29→```\\n    30→\\n    31→## Key Patterns\\n    32→\\n    33→- Every test uses `testutil.ForEachAgent` which runs it per registered agent with repo setup, concurrency gating, and timeout scaling.\\n    34→- All operations go through `RepoState` (`s.RunPrompt`, `s.Git`) so they're logged to `console.log`.\\n    35→- Use the `entire` package for CLI interactions, not raw `exec.Command`.\\n    36→- Skip tests pending CLI fixes with `t.Skip(\\\"ENT-XXX: reason\\\")`.\\n    37→\\n    38→## Adding a New Agent\\n    39→\\n    40→1. Create `agents/<name>.go` implementing the `Agent` interface.\\n    41→2. Register it in `init()` with `Register(&YourAgent{})`.\\n    42→3. Add a `Bootstrap()` method for any CI-specific setup (auth config, warmup).\\n    43→4. Add a `RegisterGate(\\\"<name>\\\", N)` call if concurrency needs limiting.\\n    44→5. Ensure the agent name is accepted by `mise run test:e2e --agent <name>`.\\n    45→6. Add the agent to `.github/workflows/e2e.yml` matrix and `e2e-isolated.yml` options.\\n    46→\\n    47→## Environment Variables\\n    48→\\n    49→| Variable | Description | Default |\\n    50→|----------|-------------|---------|\\n    51→| `E2E_AGENT` | Agent to test (`claude-code`, `gemini-cli`, `opencode`, `cursor-cli`, `copilot-cli`) | all registered |\\n    52→| `E2E_ENTIRE_BIN` | Path to a pre-built `entire` binary | builds from source |\\n    53→| `E2E_TIMEOUT` | Timeout per prompt | `2m` |\\n    54→| `E2E_KEEP_REPOS` | Set to `1` to preserve temp repos after test | unset |\\n    55→| `E2E_ARTIFACT_DIR` | Override artifact output directory | `e2e/artifacts/<timestamp>` |\\n    56→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Required for Claude Code | — |\\n    57→| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | Required for Gemini CLI | — |\\n    58→| `COPILOT_GITHUB_TOKEN` | Required for Copilot CLI (or `gh auth login`) | — |\\n    59→\\n    60→## Debugging Failures\\n    61→\\n    62→Artifacts are captured to `e2e/artifacts/` on every run (git-log, git-tree, console.log, checkpoint metadata, entire logs). Set `E2E_KEEP_REPOS=1` to preserve the temp repo — a symlink appears in the artifact dir pointing to it.\\n    63→\\n    64→Use the `debug-e2e` skill (`.claude/skills/debug-e2e/`) for a structured workflow when investigating failures.\\n    65→\\n    66→### Reading artifacts\\n    67→\\n    68→- `console.log` — full operation transcript including agent stdout/stderr\\n    69→- `git-log.txt` — commit history at time of failure\\n    70→- `git-tree.txt` — working tree state\\n    71→- `entire-logs/` — internal CLI logs\\n    72→\\n    73→### Fixing flaky tests\\n    74→\\n    75→When a test passes on retry but failed once, the problem is usually agent non-determinism, not a CLI bug. Common patterns:\\n    76→\\n    77→- **Agent asked for confirmation instead of acting**: The model output contains \\\"Does this look right?\\\" or \\\"Should I proceed?\\\". Fix: append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation, just make the change.\\\" to the prompt.\\n    78→- **Agent wrote to wrong path or created extra files**: Fix: be more explicit about exact file paths and what _not_ to do.\\n    79→- **Agent committed when it shouldn't have**: Fix: add \\\"Do not commit\\\" to the prompt.\\n    80→- **Checkpoint wait timeout**: `WaitForCheckpoint` or `WaitForCheckpointAdvanceFrom` exceeded deadline. Fix: increase the timeout argument.\\n    81→\\n    82→To diagnose: read `console.log` in the failing test's artifact directory. Compare what the agent actually did vs what the test expected.\\n    83→\\n    84→## CI Workflows\\n    85→\\n    86→- **`.github/workflows/e2e.yml`** — Runs full suite on push to main. Matrix: `[claude-code, opencode, gemini-cli, cursor-cli, copilot-cli]`.\\n    87→- **`.github/workflows/e2e-isolated.yml`** — Manual dispatch for debugging a single test. Inputs: agent + test name filter.\\n    88→\\n    89→Both workflows run `go run ./e2e/bootstrap` before tests to handle agent-specific CI setup (auth config, warmup).\\n    90→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"9209e420-3488-4a4a-96bf-c57539af2611\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.569Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a4bdb7c4ace4a825d\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Fmke2bAXdfpTGRwYQo7zXy\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01FsWns8pdZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"aea5518d-985d-4396-a9ef-fd757dbc1047\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.571Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"aea5518d-985d-4396-a9ef-fd757dbc1047\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.880Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01HJpagQVhktraPSugmaAB7x\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01X9AzbfW1cJMPamhQeyfiVn\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1/e2e/testutil/repo.go\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":23474,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":23474,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":5,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ34rbfbmUqaaSuAY35f8\",\"uuid\":\"dbbf6c4b-d2a9-4539-a5b6-7fbde0fcffbc\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a4bdb7c4ace4a825d\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Fmke2bAXdfpTGRwYQo7zXy\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01FsWns8pdZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"73d28fee-27e0-462a-8a15-42655d6e06be\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.881Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"73d28fee-27e0-462a-8a15-42655d6e06be\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01X9AzbfW1cJMPamhQeyfiVn\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→package testutil\\n     2→\\n     3→import (\\n     4→\\t\\\"context\\\"\\n     5→\\t\\\"encoding/json\\\"\\n     6→\\t\\\"errors\\\"\\n     7→\\t\\\"fmt\\\"\\n     8→\\t\\\"os\\\"\\n     9→\\t\\\"os/exec\\\"\\n    10→\\t\\\"path/filepath\\\"\\n    11→\\t\\\"strings\\\"\\n    12→\\t\\\"testing\\\"\\n    13→\\t\\\"time\\\"\\n    14→\\n    15→\\t\\\"github.com/entireio/cli/e2e/agents\\\"\\n    16→\\t\\\"github.com/entireio/cli/e2e/entire\\\"\\n    17→)\\n    18→\\n    19→const droidRepoSettingsPath = \\\".factory/settings.json\\\"\\n    20→\\n    21→// RepoState holds the working state for a single test's cloned repository.\\n    22→type RepoState struct {\\n    23→\\tAgent            agents.Agent\\n    24→\\tDir              string\\n    25→\\tArtifactDir      string\\n    26→\\tHeadBefore       string\\n    27→\\tCheckpointBefore string\\n    28→\\tConsoleLog       *os.File\\n    29→\\tsession          agents.Session // interactive session, if started via StartSession\\n    30→\\tskipArtifacts    bool           // suppresses artifact capture on scenario restart\\n    31→}\\n    32→\\n    33→// SetupRepo creates a fresh git repository in a temporary directory, seeds it\\n    34→// with an initial commit, and runs `entire enable` for the given agent.\\n    35→// Artifact capture is registered as a cleanup function.\\n    36→//\\n    37→// When E2E_KEEP_REPOS is set, the temporary directory is not cleaned up\\n    38→// so it can be inspected after the test. A symlink in the artifact dir\\n    39→// points to the preserved repo.\\n    40→func SetupRepo(t *testing.T, agent agents.Agent) *RepoState {\\n    41→\\tt.Helper()\\n    42→\\n    43→\\tkeepRepos := os.Getenv(\\\"E2E_KEEP_REPOS\\\") != \\\"\\\"\\n    44→\\n    45→\\t// Always use os.MkdirTemp instead of t.TempDir(). Go's t.TempDir()\\n    46→\\t// creates nested subdirectories (TestName.../001/) whose structure\\n    47→\\t// confuses some agents' (e.g. opencode) working-directory resolution.\\n    48→\\tdir, err := os.MkdirTemp(\\\"\\\", \\\"e2e-repo-*\\\")\\n    49→\\tif err != nil {\\n    50→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"create temp dir: %v\\\", err)\\n    51→\\t}\\n    52→\\tif keepRepos {\\n    53→\\t\\tt.Logf(\\\"E2E_KEEP_REPOS: repo will be preserved at %s\\\", dir)\\n    54→\\t} else {\\n    55→\\t\\tt.Cleanup(func() { os.RemoveAll(dir) })\\n    56→\\t}\\n    57→\\n    58→\\t// Resolve symlinks (macOS: /var -> /private/var) so paths match\\n    59→\\t// what agent CLIs see when they resolve their own CWD.\\n    60→\\tif resolved, err := filepath.EvalSymlinks(dir); err == nil {\\n    61→\\t\\tdir = resolved\\n    62→\\t}\\n    63→\\n    64→\\tGit(t, dir, \\\"init\\\")\\n    65→\\tGit(t, dir, \\\"config\\\", \\\"user.name\\\", \\\"E2E Test\\\")\\n    66→\\tGit(t, dir, \\\"config\\\", \\\"user.email\\\", \\\"e2e@test.local\\\")\\n    67→\\tGit(t, dir, \\\"commit\\\", \\\"--allow-empty\\\", \\\"-m\\\", \\\"initial commit\\\")\\n    68→\\n    69→\\tentire.Enable(t, dir, agent.EntireAgent())\\n    70→\\tif agent.Name() == \\\"factoryai-droid\\\" {\\n    71→\\t\\tif err := configureDroidRepoSettings(dir); err != nil {\\n    72→\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"configure droid repo settings: %v\\\", err)\\n    73→\\t\\t}\\n    74→\\t}\\n    75→\\tPatchSettings(t, dir, map[string]any{\\\"log_level\\\": \\\"debug\\\"})\\n    76→\\n    77→\\t// Copilot CLI blocks on a \\\"No copilot instructions found\\\" notice in fresh\\n    78→\\t// repos that lack .github/copilot-instructions.md, preventing the interactive\\n    79→\\t// prompt from appearing.\\n    80→\\tif agent.Name() == \\\"copilot-cli\\\" {\\n    81→\\t\\tghDir := filepath.Join(dir, \\\".github\\\")\\n    82→\\t\\tif err := os.MkdirAll(ghDir, 0o755); err != nil {\\n    83→\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"create .github dir: %v\\\", err)\\n    84→\\t\\t}\\n    85→\\t\\tif err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(ghDir, \\\"copilot-instructions.md\\\"), []byte(\\\"# E2E Test\\\\n\\\"), 0o644); err != nil {\\n    86→\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"write copilot-instructions.md: %v\\\", err)\\n    87→\\t\\t}\\n    88→\\t}\\n    89→\\n    90→\\t// OpenCode's non-interactive mode auto-rejects external_directory permission\\n    91→\\t// since there's no user to prompt. Write a config to allow it.\\n    92→\\tif agent.Name() == \\\"opencode\\\" {\\n    93→\\t\\tcfg := `{\\\"$schema\\\": \\\"https://opencode.ai/config.json\\\", \\\"permission\\\": {\\\"external_directory\\\": \\\"allow\\\"}}`\\n    94→\\t\\tif key := os.Getenv(\\\"ANTHROPIC_API_KEY\\\"); key != \\\"\\\" {\\n    95→\\t\\t\\tcfg = fmt.Sprintf(`{\\\"$schema\\\": \\\"https://opencode.ai/config.json\\\", \\\"permission\\\": {\\\"external_directory\\\": \\\"allow\\\"}, \\\"provider\\\": {\\\"anthropic\\\": {\\\"options\\\": {\\\"apiKey\\\": %q}}}}`, key)\\n    96→\\t\\t}\\n    97→\\t\\tif err := os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir, \\\"opencode.json\\\"), []byte(cfg+\\\"\\\\n\\\"), 0o644); err != nil {\\n    98→\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"write opencode.json: %v\\\", err)\\n    99→\\t\\t}\\n   100→\\t}\\n   101→\\n   102→\\t// Create artifact dir eagerly so console.log is written to disk\\n   103→\\t// incrementally. Even if the test is killed by a global timeout,\\n   104→\\t// partial output survives.\\n   105→\\tartDir := artifactDir(t)\\n   106→\\tconsoleLog, err := os.Create(filepath.Join(artDir, \\\"console.log\\\"))\\n   107→\\tif err != nil {\\n   108→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"create console.log: %v\\\", err)\\n   109→\\t}\\n   110→\\n   111→\\tstate := &RepoState{\\n   112→\\t\\tAgent:            agent,\\n   113→\\t\\tDir:              dir,\\n   114→\\t\\tArtifactDir:      artDir,\\n   115→\\t\\tHeadBefore:       GitOutput(t, dir, \\\"rev-parse\\\", \\\"HEAD\\\"),\\n   116→\\t\\tCheckpointBefore: GitOutput(t, dir, \\\"rev-parse\\\", \\\"entire/checkpoints/v1\\\"),\\n   117→\\t\\tConsoleLog:       consoleLog,\\n   118→\\t}\\n   119→\\n   120→\\tt.Cleanup(func() {\\n   121→\\t\\t_ = consoleLog.Close()\\n   122→\\t\\tif !state.skipArtifacts {\\n   123→\\t\\t\\tCaptureArtifacts(t, state)\\n   124→\\t\\t}\\n   125→\\t})\\n   126→\\n   127→\\treturn state\\n   128→}\\n   129→\\n   130→func configureDroidRepoSettings(repoDir string) error {\\n   131→\\thome, err := os.UserHomeDir()\\n   132→\\tif err != nil {\\n   133→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"get home dir: %w\\\", err)\\n   134→\\t}\\n   135→\\n   136→\\tglobalSettingsPath := filepath.Join(home, \\\".factory\\\", \\\"settings.json\\\")\\n   137→\\trepoSettingsPath := filepath.Join(repoDir, droidRepoSettingsPath)\\n   138→\\n   139→\\tif err := mergeDroidCustomModels(globalSettingsPath, repoSettingsPath); err != nil {\\n   140→\\t\\treturn err\\n   141→\\t}\\n   142→\\tif err := ensureGitInfoExcludeContains(repoDir, droidRepoSettingsPath); err != nil {\\n   143→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"exclude droid settings from git: %w\\\", err)\\n   144→\\t}\\n   145→\\treturn nil\\n   146→}\\n   147→\\n   148→func mergeDroidCustomModels(globalSettingsPath, repoSettingsPath string) error {\\n   149→\\tglobalSettings, err := loadJSONMap(globalSettingsPath, \\\"global droid settings\\\")\\n   150→\\tif err != nil {\\n   151→\\t\\treturn err\\n   152→\\t}\\n   153→\\n   154→\\tcustomModels, ok := globalSettings[\\\"customModels\\\"]\\n   155→\\tif !ok {\\n   156→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\n   157→\\t\\t\\t\\\"global droid settings at %s missing customModels; repo-local %s shadows global settings\\\",\\n   158→\\t\\t\\tglobalSettingsPath,\\n   159→\\t\\t\\trepoSettingsPath,\\n   160→\\t\\t)\\n   161→\\t}\\n   162→\\n   163→\\tvar models []json.RawMessage\\n   164→\\tif err := json.Unmarshal(customModels, &models); err != nil {\\n   165→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"parse customModels in %s: %w\\\", globalSettingsPath, err)\\n   166→\\t}\\n   167→\\tif len(models) == 0 {\\n   168→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"global droid settings at %s has empty customModels\\\", globalSettingsPath)\\n   169→\\t}\\n   170→\\n   171→\\trepoSettings, err := loadJSONMap(repoSettingsPath, \\\"repo-local droid settings\\\")\\n   172→\\tif err != nil {\\n   173→\\t\\treturn err\\n   174→\\t}\\n   175→\\trepoSettings[\\\"customModels\\\"] = customModels\\n   176→\\n   177→\\t// Set the active custom model so interactive mode uses the BYOK model\\n   178→\\t// instead of prompting for selection. The value must match the Model\\n   179→\\t// field from the customModels entry (not the displayName).\\n   180→\\tmodelJSON, err := json.Marshal(agents.DefaultDroidModel())\\n   181→\\tif err != nil {\\n   182→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"marshal model setting: %w\\\", err)\\n   183→\\t}\\n   184→\\trepoSettings[\\\"model\\\"] = json.RawMessage(modelJSON)\\n   185→\\n   186→\\t// High autonomy prevents Droid from asking for confirmation during\\n   187→\\t// interactive E2E tests, which would cause hangs waiting for input.\\n   188→\\trepoSettings[\\\"autonomyMode\\\"] = json.RawMessage(`\\\"auto-high\\\"`)\\n   189→\\trepoSettings[\\\"completionSound\\\"] = json.RawMessage(`\\\"off\\\"`)\\n   190→\\n   191→\\tout, err := json.MarshalIndent(repoSettings, \\\"\\\", \\\"  \\\")\\n   192→\\tif err != nil {\\n   193→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"marshal repo-local droid settings: %w\\\", err)\\n   194→\\t}\\n   195→\\tout = append(out, '\\\\n')\\n   196→\\n   197→\\tif err := os.WriteFile(repoSettingsPath, out, 0o600); err != nil {\\n   198→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"write repo-local droid settings %s: %w\\\", repoSettingsPath, err)\\n   199→\\t}\\n   200→\\treturn nil\\n   201→}\\n   202→\\n   203→func loadJSONMap(path, description string) (map[string]json.RawMessage, error) {\\n   204→\\tdata, err := os.ReadFile(path)\\n   205→\\tif err != nil {\\n   206→\\t\\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"read %s at %s: %w\\\", description, path, err)\\n   207→\\t}\\n   208→\\n   209→\\tvar parsed map[string]json.RawMessage\\n   210→\\tif err := json.Unmarshal(data, &parsed); err != nil {\\n   211→\\t\\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"parse %s at %s: %w\\\", description, path, err)\\n   212→\\t}\\n   213→\\tif parsed == nil {\\n   214→\\t\\tparsed = make(map[string]json.RawMessage)\\n   215→\\t}\\n   216→\\treturn parsed, nil\\n   217→}\\n   218→\\n   219→func ensureGitInfoExcludeContains(repoDir, entry string) error {\\n   220→\\texcludePath := filepath.Join(repoDir, \\\".git\\\", \\\"info\\\", \\\"exclude\\\")\\n   221→\\n   222→\\tdata, err := os.ReadFile(excludePath)\\n   223→\\tif err != nil && !errors.Is(err, os.ErrNotExist) {\\n   224→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"read %s: %w\\\", excludePath, err)\\n   225→\\t}\\n   226→\\n   227→\\tnormalized := strings.ReplaceAll(string(data), \\\"\\\\r\\\\n\\\", \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   228→\\tfor _, line := range strings.Split(normalized, \\\"\\\\n\\\") {\\n   229→\\t\\tif strings.TrimSpace(line) == entry {\\n   230→\\t\\t\\treturn nil\\n   231→\\t\\t}\\n   232→\\t}\\n   233→\\n   234→\\tvar b strings.Builder\\n   235→\\tif len(data) > 0 {\\n   236→\\t\\tb.Write(data)\\n   237→\\t\\tif data[len(data)-1] != '\\\\n' {\\n   238→\\t\\t\\tb.WriteByte('\\\\n')\\n   239→\\t\\t}\\n   240→\\t}\\n   241→\\tb.WriteString(entry)\\n   242→\\tb.WriteByte('\\\\n')\\n   243→\\n   244→\\tif err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Dir(excludePath), 0o755); err != nil {\\n   245→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"create %s: %w\\\", filepath.Dir(excludePath), err)\\n   246→\\t}\\n   247→\\tif err := os.WriteFile(excludePath, []byte(b.String()), 0o644); err != nil {\\n   248→\\t\\treturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"write %s: %w\\\", excludePath, err)\\n   249→\\t}\\n   250→\\treturn nil\\n   251→}\\n   252→\\n   253→// ForEachAgent runs fn as a parallel subtest for every registered agent.\\n   254→// It handles repo setup, concurrency gating, context timeout, and cleanup.\\n   255→// The timeout is scaled by each agent's TimeoutMultiplier.\\n   256→//\\n   257→// If RunPrompt detects a transient API error (e.g. rate limit, token refresh\\n   258→// failure), it panics with errScenarioRestart. ForEachAgent recovers from the\\n   259→// panic and restarts the entire scenario with a fresh repository, up to\\n   260→// maxScenarioRestarts times. This avoids stale CLI session state from the\\n   261→// failed attempt poisoning the retry.\\n   262→func ForEachAgent(t *testing.T, timeout time.Duration, fn func(t *testing.T, s *RepoState, ctx context.Context)) {\\n   263→\\tt.Helper()\\n   264→\\tt.Parallel()\\n   265→\\tall := agents.All()\\n   266→\\tif len(all) == 0 {\\n   267→\\t\\tt.Skip(\\\"no agents registered (check E2E_AGENT filter)\\\")\\n   268→\\t}\\n   269→\\tfor _, agent := range all {\\n   270→\\t\\tt.Run(agent.Name(), func(t *testing.T) {\\n   271→\\t\\t\\t// Use the global test deadline for slot wait so we don't\\n   272→\\t\\t\\t// skip prematurely — only bail if the whole binary is dying.\\n   273→\\t\\t\\tslotCtx := context.Background()\\n   274→\\t\\t\\tif deadline, ok := t.Deadline(); ok {\\n   275→\\t\\t\\t\\tvar cancel context.CancelFunc\\n   276→\\t\\t\\t\\tslotCtx, cancel = context.WithDeadline(slotCtx, deadline)\\n   277→\\t\\t\\t\\tdefer cancel()\\n   278→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   279→\\t\\t\\tif err := agents.AcquireSlot(slotCtx, agent); err != nil {\\n   280→\\t\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"timed out waiting for agent slot: %v\\\", err)\\n   281→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   282→\\t\\t\\tdefer agents.ReleaseSlot(agent)\\n   283→\\n   284→\\t\\t\\t// Per-test timeout starts after slot is acquired, scaled\\n   285→\\t\\t\\t// by the agent's multiplier (e.g. 2.5× for gemini).\\n   286→\\t\\t\\tscaled := time.Duration(float64(timeout) * agent.TimeoutMultiplier())\\n   287→\\n   288→\\t\\t\\tvar prevState *RepoState\\n   289→\\t\\t\\tfor attempt := range maxScenarioRestarts + 1 {\\n   290→\\t\\t\\t\\ts := SetupRepo(t, agent)\\n   291→\\t\\t\\t\\tctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), scaled)\\n   292→\\n   293→\\t\\t\\t\\t// On restart, suppress artifact capture from the previous\\n   294→\\t\\t\\t\\t// failed attempt so it doesn't overwrite the final one.\\n   295→\\t\\t\\t\\tif prevState != nil {\\n   296→\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tprevState.skipArtifacts = true\\n   297→\\t\\t\\t\\t}\\n   298→\\n   299→\\t\\t\\t\\trestarted := runScenario(t, s, ctx, fn)\\n   300→\\t\\t\\t\\tcancel()\\n   301→\\n   302→\\t\\t\\t\\tif !restarted {\\n   303→\\t\\t\\t\\t\\treturn\\n   304→\\t\\t\\t\\t}\\n   305→\\t\\t\\t\\tprevState = s\\n   306→\\t\\t\\t\\tif attempt >= maxScenarioRestarts {\\n   307→\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"exhausted %d scenario attempts due to transient API errors\\\", maxScenarioRestarts+1)\\n   308→\\t\\t\\t\\t}\\n   309→\\t\\t\\t\\tt.Logf(\\\"transient error, restarting scenario (attempt %d/%d)\\\", attempt+2, maxScenarioRestarts+1)\\n   310→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   311→\\t\\t})\\n   312→\\t}\\n   313→}\\n   314→\\n   315→// runScenario runs the test function and recovers from errScenarioRestart\\n   316→// panics triggered by transient API errors in RunPrompt. Returns true if\\n   317→// the scenario should be restarted with a fresh repository.\\n   318→func runScenario(t *testing.T, s *RepoState, ctx context.Context, fn func(t *testing.T, s *RepoState, ctx context.Context)) (restarted bool) {\\n   319→\\tt.Helper()\\n   320→\\tdefer func() {\\n   321→\\t\\tif r := recover(); r != nil {\\n   322→\\t\\t\\tif _, ok := r.(errScenarioRestart); ok {\\n   323→\\t\\t\\t\\trestarted = true\\n   324→\\t\\t\\t\\treturn\\n   325→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   326→\\t\\t\\tpanic(r) // re-panic for unexpected panics\\n   327→\\t\\t}\\n   328→\\t}()\\n   329→\\tfn(t, s, ctx)\\n   330→\\treturn false\\n   331→}\\n   332→\\n   333→const maxScenarioRestarts = 2 // restart up to 2 times = 3 total attempts\\n   334→\\n   335→// errScenarioRestart is panicked by RunPrompt when a transient API error is\\n   336→// detected. ForEachAgent recovers from this panic and restarts the test\\n   337→// scenario with a fresh repository, avoiding stale CLI state from the failed\\n   338→// attempt.\\n   339→type errScenarioRestart struct {\\n   340→\\tmsg string\\n   341→}\\n   342→\\n   343→// RunPrompt runs an agent prompt, logs the command and output to ConsoleLog,\\n   344→// and returns the result. If the agent reports a transient API error, it\\n   345→// panics with errScenarioRestart to trigger a full scenario restart in\\n   346→// ForEachAgent (see runScenario).\\n   347→func (s *RepoState) RunPrompt(t *testing.T, ctx context.Context, prompt string, opts ...agents.Option) (agents.Output, error) {\\n   348→\\tt.Helper()\\n   349→\\tout, err := s.Agent.RunPrompt(ctx, s.Dir, prompt, opts...)\\n   350→\\ts.logPromptResult(out)\\n   351→\\n   352→\\tif err != nil && s.Agent.IsTransientError(out, err) {\\n   353→\\t\\terrMsg := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"transient API error (stderr: %s)\\\", strings.TrimSpace(out.Stderr))\\n   354→\\t\\tt.Logf(\\\"%s — restarting scenario\\\", errMsg)\\n   355→\\t\\tfmt.Fprintf(s.ConsoleLog, \\\"> [transient] %s — restarting scenario\\\\n\\\", errMsg)\\n   356→\\t\\tpanic(errScenarioRestart{msg: errMsg})\\n   357→\\t}\\n   358→\\n   359→\\treturn out, err\\n   360→}\\n   361→\\n   362→func (s *RepoState) logPromptResult(out agents.Output) {\\n   363→\\ts.ConsoleLog.WriteString(\\\"> \\\" + out.Command + \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   364→\\ts.ConsoleLog.WriteString(\\\"stdout:\\\\n\\\" + out.Stdout + \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   365→\\ts.ConsoleLog.WriteString(\\\"stderr:\\\\n\\\" + out.Stderr + \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   366→}\\n   367→\\n   368→// Git runs a git command in the repo and logs it to ConsoleLog.\\n   369→func (s *RepoState) Git(t *testing.T, args ...string) {\\n   370→\\tt.Helper()\\n   371→\\ts.ConsoleLog.WriteString(\\\"> git \\\" + strings.Join(args, \\\" \\\") + \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   372→\\tGit(t, s.Dir, args...)\\n   373→}\\n   374→\\n   375→// StartSession starts an interactive session and registers it for pane\\n   376→// capture in artifacts. Returns nil if the agent does not support interactive\\n   377→// mode. The session is closed automatically during test cleanup.\\n   378→func (s *RepoState) StartSession(t *testing.T, ctx context.Context) agents.Session {\\n   379→\\tt.Helper()\\n   380→\\tsession, err := s.Agent.StartSession(ctx, s.Dir)\\n   381→\\tif err != nil {\\n   382→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"start session: %v\\\", err)\\n   383→\\t}\\n   384→\\tif session == nil {\\n   385→\\t\\treturn nil\\n   386→\\t}\\n   387→\\ts.session = session\\n   388→\\treturn session\\n   389→}\\n   390→\\n   391→// WaitFor waits for a pattern in the interactive session's pane and logs the\\n   392→// pane content to ConsoleLog after the wait completes (success or failure).\\n   393→func (s *RepoState) WaitFor(t *testing.T, session agents.Session, pattern string, timeout time.Duration) {\\n   394→\\tt.Helper()\\n   395→\\tcontent, err := session.WaitFor(pattern, timeout)\\n   396→\\tfmt.Fprintf(s.ConsoleLog, \\\"> pane after WaitFor(%q):\\\\n%s\\\\n\\\", pattern, content)\\n   397→\\tif err != nil {\\n   398→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"WaitFor(%q): %v\\\", pattern, err)\\n   399→\\t}\\n   400→}\\n   401→\\n   402→// Send sends input to an interactive session and logs it to ConsoleLog.\\n   403→// Fails the test on error.\\n   404→func (s *RepoState) Send(t *testing.T, session agents.Session, input string) {\\n   405→\\tt.Helper()\\n   406→\\ts.ConsoleLog.WriteString(\\\"> send: \\\" + input + \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   407→\\tif err := session.Send(input); err != nil {\\n   408→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"send failed: %v\\\", err)\\n   409→\\t}\\n   410→}\\n   411→\\n   412→// PatchSettings merges extra keys into .entire/settings.json.\\n   413→func PatchSettings(t *testing.T, dir string, extra map[string]any) {\\n   414→\\tt.Helper()\\n   415→\\tpath := filepath.Join(dir, \\\".entire\\\", \\\"settings.json\\\")\\n   416→\\tdata, err := os.ReadFile(path)\\n   417→\\tif err != nil {\\n   418→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"read settings: %v\\\", err)\\n   419→\\t}\\n   420→\\tvar settings map[string]any\\n   421→\\tif err := json.Unmarshal(data, &settings); err != nil {\\n   422→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"parse settings: %v\\\", err)\\n   423→\\t}\\n   424→\\tfor k, v := range extra {\\n   425→\\t\\tsettings[k] = v\\n   426→\\t}\\n   427→\\tout, err := json.MarshalIndent(settings, \\\"\\\", \\\"  \\\")\\n   428→\\tif err != nil {\\n   429→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"marshal settings: %v\\\", err)\\n   430→\\t}\\n   431→\\tif err := os.WriteFile(path, out, 0o644); err != nil {\\n   432→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"write settings: %v\\\", err)\\n   433→\\t}\\n   434→}\\n   435→\\n   436→// Git runs a git command in the given directory and fails the test if it\\n   437→// returns a non-zero exit code.\\n   438→func Git(t *testing.T, dir string, args ...string) {\\n   439→\\tt.Helper()\\n   440→\\n   441→\\tcmd := exec.Command(\\\"git\\\", args...)\\n   442→\\tif dir != \\\"\\\" {\\n   443→\\t\\tcmd.Dir = dir\\n   444→\\t}\\n   445→\\tcmd.Env = append(os.Environ(), \\\"ENTIRE_TEST_TTY=0\\\")\\n   446→\\n   447→\\tout, err := cmd.CombinedOutput()\\n   448→\\tif err != nil {\\n   449→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"git %s failed: %v\\\\n%s\\\", strings.Join(args, \\\" \\\"), err, out)\\n   450→\\t}\\n   451→}\\n   452→\\n   453→// GitOutput runs a git command in the given directory, returns its trimmed\\n   454→// stdout, and fails the test on error.\\n   455→func GitOutput(t *testing.T, dir string, args ...string) string {\\n   456→\\tt.Helper()\\n   457→\\n   458→\\tcmd := exec.Command(\\\"git\\\", args...)\\n   459→\\tif dir != \\\"\\\" {\\n   460→\\t\\tcmd.Dir = dir\\n   461→\\t}\\n   462→\\n   463→\\tout, err := cmd.Output()\\n   464→\\tif err != nil {\\n   465→\\t\\tvar stderr string\\n   466→\\t\\tee := &exec.ExitError{}\\n   467→\\t\\tif errors.As(err, &ee) {\\n   468→\\t\\t\\tstderr = string(ee.Stderr)\\n   469→\\t\\t}\\n   470→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"git %s failed: %v\\\\n%s\\\", strings.Join(args, \\\" \\\"), err, stderr)\\n   471→\\t}\\n   472→\\n   473→\\treturn strings.TrimSpace(string(out))\\n   474→}\\n   475→\\n   476→// NewCheckpointCommits returns the SHAs of commits added to the\\n   477→// entire/checkpoints/v1 branch since the test was set up, oldest first.\\n   478→func NewCheckpointCommits(t *testing.T, s *RepoState) []string {\\n   479→\\tt.Helper()\\n   480→\\n   481→\\tlog := GitOutput(t, s.Dir, \\\"log\\\", \\\"--reverse\\\", \\\"--format=%H\\\", s.CheckpointBefore+\\\"..entire/checkpoints/v1\\\")\\n   482→\\tif log == \\\"\\\" {\\n   483→\\t\\treturn nil\\n   484→\\t}\\n   485→\\treturn strings.Split(log, \\\"\\\\n\\\")\\n   486→}\\n   487→\\n   488→// CheckpointIDs lists all checkpoint IDs from the tree at the tip of the\\n   489→// checkpoint branch. It parses the two-level directory structure\\n   490→// ({prefix}/{suffix}/metadata.json) and returns the concatenated IDs.\\n   491→func CheckpointIDs(t *testing.T, dir string) []string {\\n   492→\\tt.Helper()\\n   493→\\tout := gitOutputSafe(dir, \\\"ls-tree\\\", \\\"-r\\\", \\\"--name-only\\\", \\\"entire/checkpoints/v1\\\")\\n   494→\\tif out == \\\"\\\" {\\n   495→\\t\\treturn nil\\n   496→\\t}\\n   497→\\tseen := map[string]bool{}\\n   498→\\tvar ids []string\\n   499→\\tfor _, line := range strings.Split(strings.TrimSpace(out), \\\"\\\\n\\\") {\\n   500→\\t\\t// Match {prefix}/{suffix}/metadata.json (top-level, not session-level)\\n   501→\\t\\tparts := strings.Split(line, \\\"/\\\")\\n   502→\\t\\tif len(parts) == 3 && parts[2] == \\\"metadata.json\\\" {\\n   503→\\t\\t\\tid := parts[0] + parts[1]\\n   504→\\t\\t\\tif !seen[id] {\\n   505→\\t\\t\\t\\tseen[id] = true\\n   506→\\t\\t\\t\\tids = append(ids, id)\\n   507→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   508→\\t\\t}\\n   509→\\t}\\n   510→\\treturn ids\\n   511→}\\n   512→\\n   513→// ReadCheckpointMetadata reads the checkpoint-level metadata.json from the\\n   514→// tip of the checkpoint branch for the given checkpoint ID.\\n   515→func ReadCheckpointMetadata(t *testing.T, dir string, checkpointID string) CheckpointMetadata {\\n   516→\\tt.Helper()\\n   517→\\n   518→\\tpath := CheckpointPath(checkpointID) + \\\"/metadata.json\\\"\\n   519→\\tblob := \\\"entire/checkpoints/v1:\\\" + path\\n   520→\\n   521→\\traw := GitOutput(t, dir, \\\"show\\\", blob)\\n   522→\\n   523→\\tvar meta CheckpointMetadata\\n   524→\\tif err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(raw), &meta); err != nil {\\n   525→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"unmarshal checkpoint metadata from %s: %v\\\", blob, err)\\n   526→\\t}\\n   527→\\n   528→\\treturn meta\\n   529→}\\n   530→\\n   531→// ReadSessionMetadata reads a session's metadata.json from the tip of the\\n   532→// checkpoint branch for the given checkpoint ID and session index.\\n   533→func ReadSessionMetadata(t *testing.T, dir string, checkpointID string, sessionIndex int) SessionMetadata {\\n   534→\\tt.Helper()\\n   535→\\n   536→\\tpath := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"%s/%d/metadata.json\\\", CheckpointPath(checkpointID), sessionIndex)\\n   537→\\tblob := \\\"entire/checkpoints/v1:\\\" + path\\n   538→\\n   539→\\traw := GitOutput(t, dir, \\\"show\\\", blob)\\n   540→\\n   541→\\tvar meta SessionMetadata\\n   542→\\tif err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(raw), &meta); err != nil {\\n   543→\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"unmarshal session metadata from %s: %v\\\", blob, err)\\n   544→\\t}\\n   545→\\n   546→\\treturn meta\\n   547→}\\n   548→\\n   549→// WaitForSessionMetadata polls until session metadata exists on the checkpoint\\n   550→// branch for the given checkpoint ID and session index, then returns it.\\n   551→// This handles the race where the checkpoint branch advances before session\\n   552→// metadata is fully committed.\\n   553→func WaitForSessionMetadata(t *testing.T, dir string, checkpointID string, sessionIndex int, timeout time.Duration) SessionMetadata {\\n   554→\\tt.Helper()\\n   555→\\n   556→\\tpath := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"%s/%d/metadata.json\\\", CheckpointPath(checkpointID), sessionIndex)\\n   557→\\tblob := \\\"entire/checkpoints/v1:\\\" + path\\n   558→\\n   559→\\tdeadline := time.Now().Add(timeout)\\n   560→\\tfor time.Now().Before(deadline) {\\n   561→\\t\\traw := gitOutputSafe(dir, \\\"show\\\", blob)\\n   562→\\t\\tif raw != \\\"\\\" {\\n   563→\\t\\t\\tvar meta SessionMetadata\\n   564→\\t\\t\\tif err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(raw), &meta); err != nil {\\n   565→\\t\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"unmarshal session metadata from %s: %v\\\", blob, err)\\n   566→\\t\\t\\t}\\n   567→\\t\\t\\treturn meta\\n   568→\\t\\t}\\n   569→\\t\\ttime.Sleep(500 * time.Millisecond)\\n   570→\\t}\\n   571→\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"session metadata %s did not appear within %s\\\", blob, timeout)\\n   572→\\treturn SessionMetadata{}\\n   573→}\\n   574→\\n   575→// SetupBareRemote creates a bare git repo, adds it as \\\"origin\\\", and pushes\\n   576→// the initial commit. Returns the bare repo path.\\n   577→func SetupBareRemote(t *testing.T, s *RepoState) string {\\n   578→\\tt.Helper()\\n   579→\\n   580→\\tvar bareDir string\\n   581→\\tif os.Getenv(\\\"E2E_KEEP_REPOS\\\") != \\\"\\\" {\\n   582→\\t\\tvar err error\\n   583→\\t\\tbareDir, err = os.MkdirTemp(\\\"\\\", \\\"e2e-bare-*\\\")\\n   584→\\t\\tif err != nil {\\n   585→\\t\\t\\tt.Fatalf(\\\"create bare remote dir: %v\\\", err)\\n   586→\\t\\t}\\n   587→\\t\\tt.Logf(\\\"E2E_KEEP_REPOS: bare remote will be preserved at %s\\\", bareDir)\\n   588→\\t} else {\\n   589→\\t\\tbareDir = t.TempDir()\\n   590→\\t}\\n   591→\\n   592→\\tGit(t, bareDir, \\\"init\\\", \\\"--bare\\\")\\n   593→\\tGit(t, s.Dir, \\\"remote\\\", \\\"add\\\", \\\"origin\\\", bareDir)\\n   594→\\tGit(t, s.Dir, \\\"push\\\", \\\"-u\\\", \\\"origin\\\", \\\"HEAD\\\")\\n   595→\\treturn bareDir\\n   596→}\\n   597→\\n   598→// GitOutputErr runs a git command and returns (output, error) without\\n   599→// failing the test. For commands expected to fail.\\n   600→func GitOutputErr(dir string, args ...string) (string, error) {\\n   601→\\tcmd := exec.Command(\\\"git\\\", args...)\\n   602→\\tif dir != \\\"\\\" {\\n   603→\\t\\tcmd.Dir = dir\\n   604→\\t}\\n   605→\\tout, err := cmd.CombinedOutput()\\n   606→\\treturn strings.TrimSpace(string(out)), err\\n   607→}\\n   608→\\n   609→// GetCheckpointTrailer extracts the Entire-Checkpoint trailer value from a\\n   610→// code commit. Returns the trimmed trailer value, or an empty string if the\\n   611→// trailer is not present.\\n   612→func GetCheckpointTrailer(t *testing.T, dir string, ref string) string {\\n   613→\\tt.Helper()\\n   614→\\n   615→\\treturn GitOutput(t, dir, \\\"log\\\", \\\"-1\\\", \\\"--format=%(trailers:key=Entire-Checkpoint,valueonly)\\\", ref)\\n   616→}\\n   617→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"768945bc-51a1-4da4-b058-05888a486fa3\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.898Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a4bdb7c4ace4a825d\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Fmke2bAXdfpTGRwYQo7zXy\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01FsWns8pdZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"9f31921e-e1be-48cc-b915-fd07fac62fcf\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:26.899Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9f31921e-e1be-48cc-b915-fd07fac62fcf\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:27.110Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01HJpagQVhktraPSugmaAB7x\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01UZZBLRujDDeBYN8p5TD8RZ\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1/docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":23474,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":23474,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":5,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ34rbfbmUqaaSuAY35f8\",\"uuid\":\"b19d6f23-9af5-4eff-b142-b9fef3b4cf72\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a4bdb7c4ace4a825d\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Fmke2bAXdfpTGRwYQo7zXy\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01FsWns8pdZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"e5c71dd3-70e6-40ff-a63e-0a24bdb0e4e1\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:27.112Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"e5c71dd3-70e6-40ff-a63e-0a24bdb0e4e1\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01UZZBLRujDDeBYN8p5TD8RZ\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Checkpoint Scenarios\\n     2→\\n     3→This document describes how the one-to-one checkpoint system handles various user workflows.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Overview\\n     6→\\n     7→The system uses:\\n     8→- **Shadow branches** (`entire/<commit-hash>-<worktree-hash>`) - temporary storage for checkpoint data\\n     9→- **FilesTouched** - accumulates files modified during the session\\n    10→- **1:1 checkpoints** - each commit gets its own unique checkpoint ID\\n    11→- **Content-aware overlap** - prevents linking commits where user reverted session changes\\n    12→\\n    13→## State Machine\\n    14→\\n    15→```mermaid\\n    16→stateDiagram-v2\\n    17→    [*] --> IDLE : SessionStart\\n    18→\\n    19→    IDLE --> ACTIVE : TurnStart (UserPromptSubmit)\\n    20→    ACTIVE --> IDLE : TurnEnd (Stop hook)\\n    21→    ACTIVE --> ACTIVE : GitCommit / Condense\\n    22→    IDLE --> IDLE : GitCommit / Condense\\n    23→\\n    24→    IDLE --> ENDED : SessionStop\\n    25→    ACTIVE --> ENDED : SessionStop\\n    26→    ENDED --> ACTIVE : TurnStart (session resume)\\n    27→    ENDED --> ENDED : GitCommit / CondenseIfFilesTouched\\n    28→```\\n    29→\\n    30→---\\n    31→\\n    32→## Scenario 1: Prompt → Changes → Prompt Finishes → User Commits\\n    33→\\n    34→The simplest workflow: user runs a prompt, Claude makes changes, prompt finishes, then user manually commits.\\n    35→\\n    36→```mermaid\\n    37→sequenceDiagram\\n    38→    participant U as User\\n    39→    participant C as Claude\\n    40→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n    41→    participant S as Session State\\n    42→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n    43→\\n    44→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n    45→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit hook\\n    46→    G->>S: InitializeSession (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n    47→    S->>S: TurnID generated\\n    48→\\n    49→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n    50→    C->>G: SaveChanges (Stop hook)\\n    51→    G->>SB: Write checkpoint (A, B, C + transcript)\\n    52→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n    53→    Note over G: TurnEnd: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n    54→\\n    55→    Note over U: Later...\\n    56→    U->>G: git commit -a\\n    57→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg hook\\n    58→    G->>S: Check FilesTouched [A, B, C]\\n    59→    G->>G: staged [A,B,C] ∩ FilesTouched → overlap ✓\\n    60→    G->>G: Generate checkpoint ID, add trailer\\n    61→\\n    62→    Note over G: PostCommit hook\\n    63→    G->>G: EventGitCommit (IDLE)\\n    64→    G->>SB: Condense to entire/checkpoints/v1\\n    65→    G->>SB: Delete shadow branch\\n    66→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n    67→```\\n    68→\\n    69→### Key Points\\n    70→- Shadow branch holds checkpoint data until user commits\\n    71→- PrepareCommitMsg adds `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer\\n    72→- PostCommit condenses to permanent storage and cleans up\\n    73→\\n    74→---\\n    75→\\n    76→## Scenario 2: Prompt Commits Within Single Turn\\n    77→\\n    78→Claude is instructed to commit changes, so the commit happens during the ACTIVE phase.\\n    79→\\n    80→```mermaid\\n    81→sequenceDiagram\\n    82→    participant U as User\\n    83→    participant C as Claude\\n    84→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n    85→    participant S as Session State\\n    86→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n    87→\\n    88→    U->>C: \\\"Make changes and commit them\\\"\\n    89→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit hook\\n    90→    G->>S: InitializeSession (→ACTIVE)\\n    91→\\n    92→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B)\\n    93→    C->>G: git add && git commit\\n    94→\\n    95→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg (no TTY = agent commit)\\n    96→    G->>G: Generate checkpoint ID, add trailer directly\\n    97→\\n    98→    Note over G: PostCommit hook (ACTIVE)\\n    99→    G->>G: EventGitCommit (ACTIVE→ACTIVE)\\n   100→    G->>SB: Condense with provisional transcript\\n   101→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs += [checkpoint-id]\\n   102→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   103→\\n   104→    C->>G: Responds with summary\\n   105→    Note over G: Stop hook\\n   106→    G->>G: HandleTurnEnd (ACTIVE→IDLE)\\n   107→    G->>G: UpdateCommitted: finalize with full transcript\\n   108→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   109→```\\n   110→\\n   111→### Key Points\\n   112→- Agent commits detected by no TTY → fast path adds trailer directly\\n   113→- **Deferred finalization**: PostCommit saves provisional transcript, HandleTurnEnd updates with full transcript\\n   114→- TurnCheckpointIDs tracks mid-turn checkpoints for finalization at stop\\n   115→\\n   116→---\\n   117→\\n   118→## Scenario 3: Claude Makes Multiple Granular Commits\\n   119→\\n   120→Claude is instructed to make granular commits, resulting in multiple commits during one turn.\\n   121→\\n   122→```mermaid\\n   123→sequenceDiagram\\n   124→    participant U as User\\n   125→    participant C as Claude\\n   126→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   127→    participant S as Session State\\n   128→\\n   129→    U->>C: \\\"Implement feature with granular commits\\\"\\n   130→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   131→\\n   132→    C->>C: Creates file A\\n   133→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add A\\\"\\n   134→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   135→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   136→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-1 (provisional)\\n   137→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1]\\n   138→\\n   139→    C->>C: Creates file B\\n   140→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add B\\\"\\n   141→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   142→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   143→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-2 (provisional)\\n   144→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1, checkpoint-2]\\n   145→\\n   146→    C->>C: Creates file C\\n   147→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add C\\\"\\n   148→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-3\\n   149→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   150→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-3 (provisional)\\n   151→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1, checkpoint-2, checkpoint-3]\\n   152→\\n   153→    C->>G: Summary response\\n   154→    Note over G: Stop hook → HandleTurnEnd\\n   155→    G->>G: Finalize ALL checkpoints with full transcript\\n   156→    Note right of G: checkpoint-1: UpdateCommitted<br/>checkpoint-2: UpdateCommitted<br/>checkpoint-3: UpdateCommitted\\n   157→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   158→```\\n   159→\\n   160→### Key Points\\n   161→- Each commit gets its own unique checkpoint ID (1:1 model)\\n   162→- All checkpoints are finalized together at turn end\\n   163→- Each checkpoint has the full session transcript for context\\n   164→\\n   165→---\\n   166→\\n   167→## Scenario 4: User Splits Changes Into Multiple Commits\\n   168→\\n   169→User decides to create multiple commits from Claude's changes after the prompt finishes.\\n   170→\\n   171→```mermaid\\n   172→sequenceDiagram\\n   173→    participant U as User\\n   174→    participant C as Claude\\n   175→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   176→    participant S as Session State\\n   177→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   178→\\n   179→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n   180→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   181→\\n   182→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C, D)\\n   183→    C->>G: SaveChanges (Stop hook)\\n   184→    G->>SB: Write checkpoint (A, B, C, D)\\n   185→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C, D]\\n   186→    Note over G: TurnEnd: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   187→\\n   188→    Note over U: User commits A, B only\\n   189→    U->>G: git add A B && git commit\\n   190→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   191→    Note over G: PostCommit (IDLE)\\n   192→    G->>G: committedFiles = {A, B}\\n   193→    G->>G: remaining = [C, D]\\n   194→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   195→    G->>SB: Carry-forward C, D to new shadow branch\\n   196→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [C, D]\\n   197→\\n   198→    Note over U: User commits C, D\\n   199→    U->>G: git add C D && git commit\\n   200→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   201→    Note over G: PostCommit (IDLE)\\n   202→    G->>G: committedFiles = {C, D}\\n   203→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   204→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   205→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   206→```\\n   207→\\n   208→### Key Points\\n   209→- **Carry-forward logic**: uncommitted files get a new shadow branch\\n   210→- Each commit gets its own checkpoint ID (1:1 model)\\n   211→- Both checkpoints link to the same session transcript\\n   212→\\n   213→### Content-Aware Carry-Forward\\n   214→\\n   215→The carry-forward logic uses **content-aware comparison** to determine which files have remaining uncommitted changes:\\n   216→\\n   217→1. **File not in commit** → definitely has remaining changes\\n   218→2. **File in commit, hash matches shadow branch** → fully committed, no carry-forward\\n   219→3. **File in commit, hash differs from shadow branch** → partial commit (e.g., `git add -p`), carry forward\\n   220→\\n   221→This enables splitting changes within a single file across multiple commits (see Scenario 7).\\n   222→\\n   223→---\\n   224→\\n   225→## Scenario 5: Partial Commit → Stash → Next Prompt\\n   226→\\n   227→User commits some changes, stashes the rest, then runs another prompt.\\n   228→\\n   229→```mermaid\\n   230→sequenceDiagram\\n   231→    participant U as User\\n   232→    participant C as Claude\\n   233→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   234→    participant S as Session State\\n   235→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   236→\\n   237→    U->>C: Prompt 1\\n   238→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   239→\\n   240→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n   241→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   242→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A, B, C)\\n   243→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n   244→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   245→\\n   246→    Note over U: User commits A only\\n   247→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   248→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   249→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   250→    G->>SB: Carry-forward B, C\\n   251→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   252→\\n   253→    Note over U: User stashes B, C\\n   254→    U->>U: git stash\\n   255→    Note right of U: B, C removed from working directory<br/>FilesTouched still = [B, C]\\n   256→\\n   257→    U->>C: Prompt 2\\n   258→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n   259→    G->>S: TurnID = new, TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   260→    Note right of G: FilesTouched NOT cleared<br/>(accumulates across prompts)\\n   261→\\n   262→    C->>C: Makes changes (D, E)\\n   263→    C->>G: SaveChanges\\n   264→    G->>SB: Add D, E to shadow branch tree\\n   265→    Note right of SB: Tree now has: B, C (old) + D, E (new)\\n   266→    G->>S: FilesTouched = merge([B,C], [D,E]) = [B,C,D,E]\\n   267→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   268→\\n   269→    Note over U: User commits D, E\\n   270→    U->>G: git add D E && git commit\\n   271→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   272→    G->>G: staged [D,E] ∩ FilesTouched [B,C,D,E] → D,E match ✓\\n   273→    G->>G: checkpoint-2 trailer added\\n   274→\\n   275→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   276→    G->>G: committedFiles = {D, E}\\n   277→    G->>G: remaining = [B, C]\\n   278→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   279→    Note right of G: Checkpoint has FULL session transcript<br/>(both Prompt 1 and Prompt 2)\\n   280→\\n   281→    G->>G: Carry-forward attempt for B, C\\n   282→    Note right of G: B, C don't exist on disk (stashed)<br/>→ removed from tree\\n   283→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   284→```\\n   285→\\n   286→### Key Points\\n   287→- **FilesTouched accumulates** across prompts (not cleared at TurnStart)\\n   288→- **Checkpoints have full session context**: D, E commit links to transcript showing BOTH prompts\\n   289→- **No wrong attribution**: Looking at checkpoint-2, you can see D, E were created by Prompt 2\\n   290→\\n   291→### Edge Case: Stashed Files Lose Shadow Content\\n   292→\\n   293→After user commits D, E, the carry-forward for B, C creates an \\\"empty\\\" checkpoint:\\n   294→- `buildTreeWithChanges` removes non-existent files (B, C are stashed) from the tree\\n   295→- A shadow branch commit is created, but its tree is just HEAD (no B, C content)\\n   296→- `FilesTouched` is set to `[B, C]` - the files are still **tracked by name**\\n   297→\\n   298→**If user later unstashes B, C and commits them:**\\n   299→- PrepareCommitMsg: staged [B, C] overlaps with FilesTouched [B, C] by filename → trailer added ✓\\n   300→- PostCommit: checkpoint is created and linked\\n   301→- But the shadow branch doesn't have the original B, C content from Prompt 1\\n   302→\\n   303→This is acceptable behavior - stashing files mid-session and committing other files first is an explicit user action. The files are still tracked, but the shadow branch content chain is broken.\\n   304→\\n   305→---\\n   306→\\n   307→## Scenario 6: Stash → Second Prompt → Unstash → Commit All\\n   308→\\n   309→User stashes files, runs another prompt, then unstashes and commits everything together.\\n   310→\\n   311→```mermaid\\n   312→sequenceDiagram\\n   313→    participant U as User\\n   314→    participant C as Claude\\n   315→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   316→    participant S as Session State\\n   317→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   318→\\n   319→    U->>C: Prompt 1\\n   320→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   321→\\n   322→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n   323→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   324→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A, B, C)\\n   325→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n   326→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   327→\\n   328→    Note over U: User commits A only\\n   329→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   330→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   331→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   332→    G->>SB: Carry-forward B, C\\n   333→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   334→\\n   335→    Note over U: User stashes B, C\\n   336→    U->>U: git stash\\n   337→    Note right of U: B, C removed from working directory<br/>Shadow branch still has B, C\\n   338→\\n   339→    U->>C: Prompt 2\\n   340→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n   341→\\n   342→    C->>C: Makes changes (D, E)\\n   343→    C->>G: Stop hook (SaveChanges)\\n   344→    G->>SB: Add D, E to existing shadow branch\\n   345→    Note right of SB: Tree: B, C (from base) + D, E (new)\\n   346→    G->>S: FilesTouched = merge([B,C], [D,E]) = [B,C,D,E]\\n   347→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   348→\\n   349→    Note over U: User unstashes B, C\\n   350→    U->>U: git stash pop\\n   351→    Note right of U: B, C back in working directory\\n   352→\\n   353→    Note over U: User commits ALL files\\n   354→    U->>G: git add B C D E && git commit\\n   355→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   356→    G->>G: staged [B,C,D,E] ∩ FilesTouched [B,C,D,E] → all match ✓\\n   357→    G->>G: checkpoint-2 trailer added\\n   358→\\n   359→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   360→    G->>G: committedFiles = {B, C, D, E}\\n   361→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   362→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   363→    Note right of G: Checkpoint includes ALL files (B,C,D,E)<br/>and FULL transcript (both prompts)\\n   364→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   365→```\\n   366→\\n   367→### Key Points\\n   368→- **Shadow branch accumulates**: D, E added on top of existing B, C from carry-forward\\n   369→- **All files tracked**: When user commits all together, all four files link to checkpoint\\n   370→- **Full session context**: Checkpoint transcript shows Prompt 1 created B, C and Prompt 2 created D, E\\n   371→\\n   372→### Contrast with Scenario 5\\n   373→\\n   374→| Scenario | User Action | Result |\\n   375→|----------|-------------|--------|\\n   376→| **5**: Commit D, E first, then B, C later | Commits D, E while B, C stashed | B, C \\\"fall out\\\" - carry-forward fails, later commit of B, C has no shadow content |\\n   377→| **6**: Commit all together after unstash | Unstashes B, C, commits B, C, D, E together | All files linked to single checkpoint |\\n   378→\\n   379→The key difference is **when the commit happens relative to the unstash**:\\n   380→- If you commit while files are stashed → those files lose their shadow branch content\\n   381→- If you unstash first, then commit → all files are preserved together\\n   382→\\n   383→---\\n   384→\\n   385→## Scenario 7: Partial Staging with `git add -p`\\n   386→\\n   387→User uses interactive staging to commit only some hunks of a file, leaving other agent changes uncommitted.\\n   388→\\n   389→```mermaid\\n   390→sequenceDiagram\\n   391→    participant U as User\\n   392→    participant C as Claude\\n   393→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   394→    participant S as Session State\\n   395→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   396→\\n   397→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n   398→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   399→\\n   400→    C->>C: Makes multiple changes to file A\\n   401→    Note right of C: A now has lines 1-100<br/>(was empty before)\\n   402→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   403→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A with lines 1-100)\\n   404→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A]\\n   405→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   406→\\n   407→    Note over U: User stages partial content\\n   408→    U->>G: git add -p A\\n   409→    Note right of U: Stages only lines 1-50<br/>Worktree still has 1-100\\n   410→\\n   411→    U->>G: git commit\\n   412→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   413→\\n   414→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   415→    G->>G: committedFiles = {A}\\n   416→    G->>G: Content check: committed A (lines 1-50)\\n   417→    G->>G: Shadow A hash ≠ committed A hash\\n   418→    G->>G: remaining = [A] (has uncommitted changes)\\n   419→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   420→    G->>SB: Carry-forward A to new shadow branch\\n   421→    Note right of SB: New shadow has A with<br/>current worktree (lines 1-100)\\n   422→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A]\\n   423→\\n   424→    Note over U: User commits remaining\\n   425→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   426→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   427→\\n   428→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   429→    G->>G: Content check: committed A == shadow A\\n   430→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   431→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   432→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   433→```\\n   434→\\n   435→### Key Points\\n   436→- **Content-aware carry-forward**: Compares git blob hashes, not just filenames\\n   437→- Partial staging (`git add -p`) within a single file is detected\\n   438→- Each commit gets proper attribution, even when splitting one file's changes\\n   439→\\n   440→### How Content Comparison Works\\n   441→\\n   442→```mermaid\\n   443→flowchart TD\\n   444→    A[PostCommit: Carry-forward check] --> B{File in committedFiles?}\\n   445→    B -->|No| C[✓ Add to remaining<br/>File not committed at all]\\n   446→    B -->|Yes| D[Get shadow branch file hash]\\n   447→    D --> E{Shadow file exists?}\\n   448→    E -->|No| F[Skip file<br/>Nothing to compare against]\\n   449→    E -->|Yes| G{Committed hash == shadow hash?}\\n   450→    G -->|Yes| H[Skip file<br/>Fully committed]\\n   451→    G -->|No| I[✓ Add to remaining<br/>Partial commit detected]\\n   452→\\n   453→    C --> J[Carry forward remaining files]\\n   454→    I --> J\\n   455→```\\n   456→\\n   457→---\\n   458→\\n   459→## Content-Aware Overlap Detection\\n   460→\\n   461→Prevents linking commits where user reverted session changes and wrote different content.\\n   462→\\n   463→```mermaid\\n   464→flowchart TD\\n   465→    A[PostCommit: Check files overlap] --> B{File in commit AND in FilesTouched?}\\n   466→    B -->|No| Z[No checkpoint trailer]\\n   467→    B -->|Yes| C{File existed in parent commit?}\\n   468→    C -->|Yes: Modified file| D[✓ Counts as overlap<br/>User edited session's work]\\n   469→    C -->|No: New file| E{Content hash matches shadow branch?}\\n   470→    E -->|Yes| F[✓ Counts as overlap<br/>Session's content preserved]\\n   471→    E -->|No| G[✗ No overlap<br/>User reverted & replaced]\\n   472→\\n   473→    D --> H[Add checkpoint trailer]\\n   474→    F --> H\\n   475→    G --> Z\\n   476→```\\n   477→\\n   478→### Example: Reverted and Replaced\\n   479→\\n   480→```mermaid\\n   481→sequenceDiagram\\n   482→    participant U as User\\n   483→    participant C as Claude\\n   484→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   485→\\n   486→    C->>C: Creates file X with content \\\"hello\\\"\\n   487→    Note over G: Shadow branch: X (hash: abc123)\\n   488→\\n   489→    U->>U: Reverts: git checkout -- X\\n   490→    U->>U: Writes completely different content\\n   491→    Note right of U: X now has content \\\"world\\\"<br/>(hash: def456)\\n   492→\\n   493→    U->>G: git add X && git commit\\n   494→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   495→    G->>G: X in FilesTouched? Yes\\n   496→    G->>G: X is new file (not in parent)\\n   497→    G->>G: Compare hashes: abc123 ≠ def456\\n   498→    G->>G: Content mismatch → NO overlap\\n   499→    Note over G: No Entire-Checkpoint trailer added\\n   500→```\\n   501→\\n   502→---\\n   503→\\n   504→## Summary Table\\n   505→\\n   506→| Scenario | When Checkpoint Created | Checkpoint Contains | Key Mechanism |\\n   507→|----------|------------------------|---------------------|---------------|\\n   508→| 1. User commits after prompt | PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript | Normal condensation |\\n   509→| 2. Claude commits in turn | PostCommit (ACTIVE) + HandleTurnEnd | Full transcript (finalized at stop) | Deferred finalization |\\n   510→| 3. Multiple Claude commits | Each PostCommit (ACTIVE) + HandleTurnEnd | Full transcript per checkpoint | TurnCheckpointIDs tracking |\\n   511→| 4. User splits commits | Each PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript per checkpoint | Content-aware carry-forward |\\n   512→| 5. Partial commit + stash + new prompt + commit new | PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript (both prompts) | FilesTouched accumulation, stashed files \\\"fall out\\\" |\\n   513→| 6. Stash + new prompt + unstash + commit all | PostCommit (IDLE) | All files + full transcript | Shadow branch accumulation |\\n   514→| 7. Partial staging with `git add -p` | Each PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript per checkpoint | Content-aware carry-forward (hash comparison) |\\n   515→\\n   516→---\\n   517→\\n   518→## Known Caveats\\n   519→\\n   520→### 1. Redundant Transcript Data Across Commits\\n   521→\\n   522→Each checkpoint stores the **full session transcript** up to that point. If a session results in multiple commits (Scenarios 3, 4, 5, 6), each checkpoint contains overlapping transcript data.\\n   523→\\n   524→**Example**: Session with 3 commits\\n   525→- Checkpoint 1: transcript lines 1-100\\n   526→- Checkpoint 2: transcript lines 1-200 (includes 1-100 again)\\n   527→- Checkpoint 3: transcript lines 1-300 (includes 1-200 again)\\n   528→\\n   529→**Trade-off**: This simplifies checkpoint retrieval (each is self-contained) at the cost of storage efficiency.\\n   530→\\n   531→### 2. Token Usage Sums Are Misleading\\n   532→\\n   533→Each checkpoint's `metadata.json` contains cumulative token usage for the entire session up to that point. Summing token counts across multiple checkpoints from the same session **double-counts tokens**.\\n   534→\\n   535→**Example**:\\n   536→- Checkpoint 1: 10,000 tokens (session total so far)\\n   537→- Checkpoint 2: 25,000 tokens (session total so far)\\n   538→- Naive sum: 35,000 tokens ❌\\n   539→- Actual usage: 25,000 tokens ✓\\n   540→\\n   541→**Correct approach**: Use the token count from the **last checkpoint** of a session, or track incremental deltas separately.\\n   542→\\n   543→### 3. Stashed Files Lose Shadow Content\\n   544→\\n   545→As described in Scenario 5, if files are stashed and other files are committed first, the stashed files lose their content in the shadow branch. They remain tracked by filename in `FilesTouched`, but subsequent checkpoints won't have the original file content preserved.\\n   546→\\n   547→### 4. No Per-File Prompt Attribution\\n   548→\\n   549→Checkpoints don't explicitly tag which prompt created which file. To determine this, you must parse the transcript and correlate `tool_use` entries with preceding `user` messages. The `files_touched` list in metadata is cumulative across all prompts.\\n   550→\\n   551→### 5. Carry-Forward Checkpoints Include Full Transcript\\n   552→\\n   553→When files are carried forward (Scenario 4), `CheckpointTranscriptStart` is reset to 0. This means each carry-forward checkpoint includes the **entire transcript**, not just new content since the last checkpoint.\\n   554→\\n   555→**Impact**: For long sessions with many partial commits, checkpoint storage grows linearly with session length × number of commits.\\n   556→\\n   557→### 6. Crash Before HandleTurnEnd Leaves Provisional Transcripts\\n   558→\\n   559→In Scenarios 2 and 3 (Claude commits during turn), checkpoints are saved with \\\"provisional\\\" transcripts during PostCommit. The full transcript is written at HandleTurnEnd (Stop hook).\\n   560→\\n   561→If the session crashes or is killed before the Stop hook fires:\\n   562→- Checkpoints exist with partial transcripts\\n   563→- `TurnCheckpointIDs` in session state tracks which need finalization\\n   564→- Next session start does **not** automatically finalize orphaned checkpoints\\n   565→\\n   566→### 7. Two Different Content-Aware Checks\\n   567→\\n   568→The system uses two separate content-aware checks with different purposes:\\n   569→\\n   570→**A. Overlap Detection** (`filesOverlapWithContent`) - Determines if commit should be linked to session:\\n   571→- Only applies to **newly created files**\\n   572→- Modified files (existed in parent) **always count as overlap**\\n   573→- Used in PrepareCommitMsg/PostCommit for non-ACTIVE sessions\\n   574→- **Purpose**: Prevent linking commits where user reverted session content\\n   575→\\n   576→**B. Carry-Forward Detection** (`filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`) - Determines which files to carry forward:\\n   577→- Applies to **all committed files**\\n   578→- Compares committed content hash vs shadow branch hash\\n   579→- Hash mismatch = partial commit, file carried forward\\n   580→- **Purpose**: Enable splitting changes within a file across commits (Scenario 7)\\n   581→\\n   582→### 8. Carry-Forward Content Superseded by New Prompts\\n   583→\\n   584→When files are carried forward and then a new prompt modifies the same file:\\n   585→- The shadow branch gets the **new** content (from the new prompt's SaveChanges)\\n   586→- The carried-forward content is overwritten\\n   587→- Subsequent commits compare against the **new prompt's content**, not the original carried-forward content\\n   588→\\n   589→**Example**:\\n   590→1. Prompt 1: Agent writes 100 lines to file A\\n   591→2. User commits 50 lines via `git add -p`\\n   592→3. Carry-forward: A (with 100 lines) goes to new shadow branch\\n   593→4. Prompt 2: Agent adds 50 more lines to A (now 150 lines total in worktree)\\n   594→5. SaveChanges: Shadow branch now has A with 150 lines\\n   595→6. User commits: Comparison is against 150 lines, not original 100 lines\\n   596→\\n   597→This is correct behavior - the shadow branch reflects the **current combined state** of the session's work.\\n   598→\\n   599→### 9. Automatic Cleanup During Normal Operations\\n   600→\\n   601→Most orphaned data is cleaned up automatically:\\n   602→\\n   603→- **Shadow branches**: Deleted after condensation if no other sessions reference them\\n   604→- **Session states**: Cleaned up during session listing when shadow branch no longer exists (and session is not ACTIVE, has no `LastCheckpointID`)\\n   605→\\n   606→For anything that slips through, run `entire clean` manually:\\n   607→\\n   608→```bash\\n   609→entire clean          # Preview orphaned items\\n   610→entire clean --force  # Delete orphaned items\\n   611→```\\n   612→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"446bcaa4-f8c2-40d7-9b57-8a738df54052\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:27.133Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a4bdb7c4ace4a825d\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Fmke2bAXdfpTGRwYQo7zXy\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01FsWns8pdZuMm4UbMAw2KVW\",\"uuid\":\"cc7d30a2-3721-4e79-8669-c9b2b86c5ca8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T13:40:27.180Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"36636388-6a2e-45ad-ac63-5d08a06fbf23\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/e2e-with-git-remote\",\"slug\":\"dazzling-moseying-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"cc7d30a2-3721-4e79-8669-c9b2