ecovery. All tests use local bare repos as remotes (no network). No E2E/agent tests needed — hook plumbing level is sufficient.\\n     6→\\n     7→## Goals\\n     8→\\n     9→- Verify the PrePush hook correctly pushes `entire/checkpoints/v1` and `entire/trails/v1` to the right remotes\\n    10→- Verify checkpoint_remote config routes checkpoints to a separate remote while trails stay on origin\\n    11→- Verify clone-and-resume: cloning a repo fetches checkpoint metadata and allows session continuation\\n    12→- Verify non-fast-forward recovery (fetch + merge + retry) when two clones race\\n    13→- Verify graceful degradation when checkpoint remote is unreachable\\n    14→- Verify session discovery (`entire sessions` / `entire log`) works after clone with fetched metadata\\n    15→\\n    16→## Test Location\\n    17→\\n    18→All tests go in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/` using the existing `TestEnv` infrastructure, extended with bare remote helpers.\\n    19→\\n    20→## Infrastructure Additions\\n    21→\\n    22→### Must Have (P0)\\n    23→\\n    24→- [ ] **Add bare remote helpers to integration test `testenv.go`**\\n    25→  - `env.SetupBareRemote()` — creates bare repo, adds as \\\"origin\\\", pushes HEAD (mirrors E2E helper)\\n    26→  - `env.SetupNamedBareRemote(name)` — same but with custom remote name (for checkpoint_remote scenarios)\\n    27→  - `env.CloneFrom(bareDir)` — clones bare repo into new temp dir, returns new `TestEnv`\\n    28→  - `env.BranchExistsOnRemote(bareDir, branch)` — checks if branch exists on bare remote\\n    29→  - `env.PatchSettings(extra map[string]any)` — merges keys into `.entire/settings.json` (like E2E `PatchSettings`)\\n    30→\\n    31→## Functional Requirements\\n    32→\\n    33→### P0 — PrePush Basic Flow\\n    34→\\n    35→These test the core push path that every user hits.\\n    36→\\n    37→- [ ] **Test: PrePush pushes checkpoint branch to origin**\\n    38→  Setup: bare remote as origin → session → SaveStep → condense (simulate post-commit) → PrePush(\\\"origin\\\")\\n    39→  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` exists on bare remote, commit tree contains checkpoint metadata\\n    40→\\n    41→- [ ] **Test: PrePush pushes trails branch to origin**\\n    42→  Same setup, also verify `entire/trails/v1` arrives on bare remote\\n    43→\\n    44→- [ ] **Test: PrePush is no-op when no checkpoints exist**\\n    45→  Setup: bare remote → no session activity → PrePush(\\\"origin\\\")\\n    46→  Assert: no `entire/checkpoints/v1` on remote, no error\\n    47→\\n    48→- [ ] **Test: PrePush is no-op when already pushed (idempotent)**\\n    49→  Setup: push once → push again with no new checkpoints\\n    50→  Assert: second push succeeds, remote ref unchanged\\n    51→\\n    52→### P0 — Checkpoint Remote Config\\n    53→\\n    54→These test the separate checkpoint remote routing, which is the key feature for the clone-and-resume flow.\\n    55→\\n    56→- [ ] **Test: checkpoint_remote routes checkpoints to separate remote**\\n    57→  Setup: two bare remotes (origin + checkpoint-remote) → configure `strategy_options.checkpoint_remote: {provider: \\\"github\\\", repo: \\\"org/checkpoints\\\"}` → BUT since we use local paths, we need to set the checkpoint remote URL directly via the push remote URL derivation. Alternative: set origin's push URL to an SSH-like format and have the checkpoint remote derive from it. Simpler approach: test `resolvePushSettings` integration with real remotes — set origin URL, configure checkpoint_remote, call PrePush, verify checkpoints land on checkpoint remote URL (bare repo path) and trails land on origin.\\n    58→\\n    59→  **Concrete approach:** Create two bare repos. Configure origin normally. For checkpoint_remote, since `deriveCheckpointURL` derives from the push remote's protocol+host, and we're using local paths (not URLs), we need to either:\\n    60→  - (a) Call `pushBranchIfNeeded` directly with the bare repo path as target, OR\\n    61→  - (b) Mock the settings resolution to return the second bare repo path as `checkpointURL`\\n    62→\\n    63→  Recommended: Test at the `PrePush` level by patching settings so `checkpoint_remote` resolves to the second bare repo. This tests the full routing logic.\\n    64→\\n    65→  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` on checkpoint bare remote (not on origin), `entire/trails/v1` on origin (not on checkpoint remote)\\n    66→\\n    67→- [ ] **Test: push_sessions: false disables checkpoint push, trails still pushed**\\n    68→  Setup: bare remote → configure `push_sessions: false` → session + condense → PrePush\\n    69→  Assert: no `entire/checkpoints/v1` on remote, `entire/trails/v1` IS on remote\\n    70→\\n    71→- [ ] **Test: fork detection skips checkpoint_remote, falls back to origin**\\n    72→  Setup: configure checkpoint_remote with different owner than push remote → PrePush\\n    73→  Assert: checkpoints pushed to origin, not to checkpoint remote URL\\n    74→\\n    75→### P0 — Clone and Resume\\n    76→\\n    77→This is the primary user story: clone a repo where sessions were previously pushed, and resume working.\\n    78→\\n    79→- [ ] **Test: clone fetches checkpoint metadata on first session start**\\n    80→  Setup: repo A with bare remote → session → condense → push (checkpoints on remote) → clone into repo B → start new session in B (triggers `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing`)\\n    81→  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` exists locally in clone, contains checkpoint data from repo A\\n    82→\\n    83→- [ ] **Test: session listing works after clone**\\n    84→  Setup: same as above (clone with fetched metadata)\\n    85→  Assert: `ListCheckpoints()` returns checkpoints from the original repo's sessions\\n    86→\\n    87→- [ ] **Test: session log retrieval works after clone**\\n    88→  Setup: same as above\\n    89→  Assert: `getCheckpointLog(cpID)` returns transcript content from original session\\n    90→\\n    91→- [ ] **Test: clone + new session + push appends to existing metadata**\\n    92→  Setup: clone from remote with existing checkpoints → new session in clone → condense → push\\n    93→  Assert: remote's `entire/checkpoints/v1` now has BOTH original and new checkpoint data\\n    94→\\n    95→- [ ] **Test: clone with checkpoint_remote fetches from checkpoint URL**\\n    96→  Setup: push checkpoints to separate checkpoint remote → clone from origin (no checkpoints) → configure checkpoint_remote in clone → start session (triggers fetch from checkpoint URL)\\n    97→  Assert: clone has checkpoint metadata fetched from checkpoint remote, not origin\\n    98→\\n    99→### P1 — Non-Fast-Forward Recovery\\n   100→\\n   101→These test the race condition where two clones push to the same remote.\\n   102→\\n   103→- [ ] **Test: concurrent push — second pusher fetches, merges, retries**\\n   104→  Setup: two clones (A and B) of same bare remote → both create sessions + condense → A pushes → B pushes (gets non-fast-forward) → B should fetch+merge+retry\\n   105→  Assert: remote has checkpoints from BOTH A and B, B's local branch has merge commit with two parents\\n   106→\\n   107→- [ ] **Test: concurrent push with disconnected metadata (empty-orphan recovery)**\\n   108→  Setup: two clones where one has the empty-orphan bug artifact → both push\\n   109→  Assert: reconciliation repairs the disconnected history, remote has clean linear-ish history\\n   110→\\n   111→### P1 — Graceful Degradation\\n   112→\\n   113→- [ ] **Test: unreachable checkpoint remote — push continues silently**\\n   114→  Setup: configure checkpoint_remote pointing to non-existent path → session + condense → PrePush\\n   115→  Assert: no error returned (hooks must not fail), trails still pushed to origin, warning logged\\n   116→\\n   117→- [ ] **Test: unreachable checkpoint remote — fetch on clone is silent**\\n   118→  Setup: clone from origin → configure checkpoint_remote to non-existent path → start session\\n   119→  Assert: session starts normally, no error, `entire/checkpoints/v1` not created locally (nothing to fetch)\\n   120→\\n   121→- [ ] **Test: fetch timeout does not block push**\\n   122→  Verify that `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` has a bounded timeout (30s) and doesn't hang indefinitely. May be hard to test without a slow remote — could be P2 or skip.\\n   123→\\n   124→### P2 — Edge Cases\\n   125→\\n   126→- [ ] **Test: PrePush with URL target (not remote name)**\\n   127→  Setup: call `pushBranchIfNeeded` with bare repo path as URL directly\\n   128→  Assert: push succeeds, no remote-tracking ref check (URL path skips optimization)\\n   129→\\n   130→- [ ] **Test: fetch is one-time — second call is no-op**\\n   131→  Setup: fetch metadata branch → call fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing again\\n   132→  Assert: second call returns immediately (branch exists locally), no git fetch executed\\n   133→\\n   134→- [ ] **Test: push after rebase (shadow branch migration + push)**\\n   135→  Setup: session → checkpoint on shadow branch → simulate rebase (HEAD changes) → shadow branch migrates → condense → push\\n   136→  Assert: checkpoint metadata correctly references new base commit, pushes cleanly\\n   137→\\n   138→## Out of Scope\\n   139→\\n   140→- E2E tests with real agents (Vogon or otherwise) — integration level is sufficient\\n   141→- Testing actual SSH/HTTPS authentication — we use local path remotes\\n   142→- Testing the `entire push` CLI command (if it exists) — we test the strategy method directly\\n   143→- Performance testing of push/fetch operations\\n   144→- Multi-worktree push scenarios (separate effort)\\n   145→\\n   146→## Dependencies\\n   147→\\n   148→- Existing integration test infrastructure (`testenv.go`, `TestEnv`)\\n   149→- Strategy implementation (`push_common.go`, `checkpoint_remote.go`, `manual_commit_push.go`)\\n   150→- Checkpoint store (`checkpoint/` package)\\n   151→- Session state management (`session/` package)\\n   152→\\n   153→## Open Questions\\n   154→\\n   155→- [ ] How to make `resolvePushSettings` use a local bare repo path as `checkpointURL` in tests? Options: (a) patch settings + set origin URL to trigger derivation, (b) test at `pushBranchIfNeeded` level with explicit paths, (c) add test-only override. Need to check if `deriveCheckpointURL` works with local paths or only real URLs.\\n   156→- [ ] Should we test the `entire/trails/v1` branch content (not just existence)? Trails are always pushed to origin — do we need to verify trail content, or just that the branch arrives?\\n   157→- [ ] The `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` one-time behavior — is it per-process or persisted? If per-process, the clone test naturally exercises it (fresh process). If persisted, we need to reset state between calls.\\n   158→\\n   159→## Acceptance Criteria\\n   160→\\n   161→- All P0 tests pass with `mise run test:integration`\\n   162→- Tests use isolated temp repos with bare remotes (no network, no real repo pollution)\\n   163→- Tests follow existing conventions: `t.Parallel()`, `testutil.InitRepo`, feature branch env\\n   164→- No flaky async waits — integration tests call strategy methods directly (synchronous)\\n   165→- CI (`mise run test:ci`) passes with the new tests\\n   166→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"d836f3c4-60fd-48da-8713-6fb35c04ef1c\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T14:37:13.616Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1/docs/requirements/remote-operations-tests/README.md\",\"content\":\"# Remote Operations Test Coverage\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nAdd integration tests for git remote operations: pushing checkpoint/trails branches, fetching metadata from checkpoint remotes, clone-and-resume workflows, and non-fast-forward recovery. All tests use local bare repos as remotes (no network). No E2E/agent tests needed — hook plumbing level is sufficient.\\n\\n## Goals\\n\\n- Verify the PrePush hook correctly pushes `entire/checkpoints/v1` and `entire/trails/v1` to the right remotes\\n- Verify checkpoint_remote config routes checkpoints to a separate remote while trails stay on origin\\n- Verify clone-and-resume: cloning a repo fetches checkpoint metadata and allows session continuation\\n- Verify non-fast-forward recovery (fetch + merge + retry) when two clones race\\n- Verify graceful degradation when checkpoint remote is unreachable\\n- Verify session discovery (`entire sessions` / `entire log`) works after clone with fetched metadata\\n\\n## Test Location\\n\\nAll tests go in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/` using the existing `TestEnv` infrastructure, extended with bare remote helpers.\\n\\n## Infrastructure Additions\\n\\n### Must Have (P0)\\n\\n- [ ] **Add bare remote helpers to integration test `testenv.go`**\\n  - `env.SetupBareRemote()` — creates bare repo, adds as \\\"origin\\\", pushes HEAD (mirrors E2E helper)\\n  - `env.SetupNamedBareRemote(name)` — same but with custom remote name (for checkpoint_remote scenarios)\\n  - `env.CloneFrom(bareDir)` — clones bare repo into new temp dir, returns new `TestEnv`\\n  - `env.BranchExistsOnRemote(bareDir, branch)` — checks if branch exists on bare remote\\n  - `env.PatchSettings(extra map[string]any)` — merges keys into `.entire/settings.json` (like E2E `PatchSettings`)\\n\\n## Functional Requirements\\n\\n### P0 — PrePush Basic Flow\\n\\nThese test the core push path that every user hits.\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: PrePush pushes checkpoint branch to origin**\\n  Setup: bare remote as origin → session → SaveStep → condense (simulate post-commit) → PrePush(\\\"origin\\\")\\n  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` exists on bare remote, commit tree contains checkpoint metadata\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: PrePush pushes trails branch to origin**\\n  Same setup, also verify `entire/trails/v1` arrives on bare remote\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: PrePush is no-op when no checkpoints exist**\\n  Setup: bare remote → no session activity → PrePush(\\\"origin\\\")\\n  Assert: no `entire/checkpoints/v1` on remote, no error\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: PrePush is no-op when already pushed (idempotent)**\\n  Setup: push once → push again with no new checkpoints\\n  Assert: second push succeeds, remote ref unchanged\\n\\n### P0 — Checkpoint Remote Config\\n\\nThese test the separate checkpoint remote routing, which is the key feature for the clone-and-resume flow.\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: checkpoint_remote routes checkpoints to separate remote**\\n  Setup: two bare remotes (origin + checkpoint-remote) → configure `strategy_options.checkpoint_remote: {provider: \\\"github\\\", repo: \\\"org/checkpoints\\\"}` → BUT since we use local paths, we need to set the checkpoint remote URL directly via the push remote URL derivation. Alternative: set origin's push URL to an SSH-like format and have the checkpoint remote derive from it. Simpler approach: test `resolvePushSettings` integration with real remotes — set origin URL, configure checkpoint_remote, call PrePush, verify checkpoints land on checkpoint remote URL (bare repo path) and trails land on origin.\\n\\n  **Concrete approach:** Create two bare repos. Configure origin normally. For checkpoint_remote, since `deriveCheckpointURL` derives from the push remote's protocol+host, and we're using local paths (not URLs), we need to either:\\n  - (a) Call `pushBranchIfNeeded` directly with the bare repo path as target, OR\\n  - (b) Mock the settings resolution to return the second bare repo path as `checkpointURL`\\n\\n  Recommended: Test at the `PrePush` level by patching settings so `checkpoint_remote` resolves to the second bare repo. This tests the full routing logic.\\n\\n  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` on checkpoint bare remote (not on origin), `entire/trails/v1` on origin (not on checkpoint remote)\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: push_sessions: false disables checkpoint push, trails still pushed**\\n  Setup: bare remote → configure `push_sessions: false` → session + condense → PrePush\\n  Assert: no `entire/checkpoints/v1` on remote, `entire/trails/v1` IS on remote\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: fork detection skips checkpoint_remote, falls back to origin**\\n  Setup: configure checkpoint_remote with different owner than push remote → PrePush\\n  Assert: checkpoints pushed to origin, not to checkpoint remote URL\\n\\n### P0 — Clone and Resume\\n\\nThis is the primary user story: clone a repo where sessions were previously pushed, and resume working.\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: clone fetches checkpoint metadata on first session start**\\n  Setup: repo A with bare remote → session → condense → push (checkpoints on remote) → clone into repo B → start new session in B (triggers `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing`)\\n  Assert: `entire/checkpoints/v1` exists locally in clone, contains checkpoint data from repo A\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: session listing works after clone**\\n  Setup: same as above (clone with fetched metadata)\\n  Assert: `ListCheckpoints()` returns checkpoints from the original repo's sessions\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: session log retrieval works after clone**\\n  Setup: same as above\\n  Assert: `getCheckpointLog(cpID)` returns transcript content from original session\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: clone + new session + push appends to existing metadata**\\n  Setup: clone from remote with existing checkpoints → new session in clone → condense → push\\n  Assert: remote's `entire/checkpoints/v1` now has BOTH original and new checkpoint data\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: clone with checkpoint_remote fetches from checkpoint URL**\\n  Setup: push checkpoints to separate checkpoint remote → clone from origin (no checkpoints) → configure checkpoint_remote in clone → start session (triggers fetch from checkpoint URL)\\n  Assert: clone has checkpoint metadata fetched from checkpoint remote, not origin\\n\\n### P1 — Non-Fast-Forward Recovery\\n\\nThese test the race condition where two clones push to the same remote.\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: concurrent push — second pusher fetches, merges, retries**\\n  Setup: two clones (A and B) of same bare remote → both create sessions + condense → A pushes → B pushes (gets non-fast-forward) → B should fetch+merge+retry\\n  Assert: remote has checkpoints from BOTH A and B, B's local branch has merge commit with two parents\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: concurrent push with disconnected metadata (empty-orphan recovery)**\\n  Setup: two clones where one has the empty-orphan bug artifact → both push\\n  Assert: reconciliation repairs the disconnected history, remote has clean linear-ish history\\n\\n### P1 — Graceful Degradation\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: unreachable checkpoint remote — push continues silently**\\n  Setup: configure checkpoint_remote pointing to non-existent path → session + condense → PrePush\\n  Assert: no error returned (hooks must not fail), trails still pushed to origin, warning logged\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: unreachable checkpoint remote — fetch on clone is silent**\\n  Setup: clone from origin → configure checkpoint_remote to non-existent path → start session\\n  Assert: session starts normally, no error, `entire/checkpoints/v1` not created locally (nothing to fetch)\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: fetch timeout does not block push**\\n  Verify that `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` has a bounded timeout (30s) and doesn't hang indefinitely. May be hard to test without a slow remote — could be P2 or skip.\\n\\n### P2 — Edge Cases\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: PrePush with URL target (not remote name)**\\n  Setup: call `pushBranchIfNeeded` with bare repo path as URL directly\\n  Assert: push succeeds, no remote-tracking ref check (URL path skips optimization)\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: fetch is one-time — second call is no-op**\\n  Setup: fetch metadata branch → call fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing again\\n  Assert: second call returns immediately (branch exists locally), no git fetch executed\\n\\n- [ ] **Test: push after rebase (shadow branch migration + push)**\\n  Setup: session → checkpoint on shadow branch → simulate rebase (HEAD changes) → shadow branch migrates → condense → push\\n  Assert: checkpoint metadata correctly references new base commit, pushes cleanly\\n\\n## Out of Scope\\n\\n- E2E tests with real agents (Vogon or otherwise) — integration level is sufficient\\n- Testing actual SSH/HTTPS authentication — we use local path remotes\\n- Testing the `entire push` CLI command (if it exists) — we test the strategy method directly\\n- Performance testing of push/fetch operations\\n- Multi-worktree push scenarios (separate effort)\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n\\n- Existing integration test infrastructure (`testenv.go`, `TestEnv`)\\n- Strategy implementation (`push_common.go`, `checkpoint_remote.go`, `manual_commit_push.go`)\\n- Checkpoint store (`checkpoint/` package)\\n- Session state management (`session/` package)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n\\n- [ ] How to make `resolvePushSettings` use a local bare repo path as `checkpointURL` in tests? Options: (a) patch settings + set origin URL to trigger derivation, (b) test at `pushBranchIfNeeded` level with explicit paths, (c) add test-only override. Need to check if `deriveCheckpointURL` works with local paths or only real URLs.\\n- [ ] Should we test the `entire/trails/v1` branch content (not just existence)? Trails are always pushed to origin — do we need to verify trail content, or just that the branch arrives?\\n- [ ] The `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` one-time behavior — is it per-process or persisted? If per-process, the clone test naturally exercises it (fresh process). If persisted, we need to reset state between calls.\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n\\n- All P0 tests pass with `mise run test:integration`\\n- Tests use isolated temp repos with bare remotes (no network, no real repo pollution)\\n- Tests follow existing conventions: `t.Parallel()`, `testutil.InitRepo`, feature branch env\\n- No flaky async waits — integration tests call strategy methods directly (synchronous)\\n- CI (`mise run test:ci`) passes with the new tests\\n\",\"numLines\":166,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":166}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"9908f6d4-1c61-4c35-8d60-51f70319e09c\",\"userType\":\"ex