-otter\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"4ed32d8c-4e8a-4026-b5d3-b34213ae0d88\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T15:48:19.228Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Y6CFDcXqsacphzKrA2WDRb\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01JhMEGSNGN9GEXbDuvVkJ8M\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1/docs/requirements/remote-operations-tests/review-01.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 01\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-14\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Files Reviewed\\n\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/testenv.go` (diff: +186 lines of infrastructure helpers)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/remote_operations_test.go` (new file, 722 lines)\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nNo previous reviews.\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:630-644] `runPrePushInDir` uses `testutil.GitIsolatedEnv()` instead of `env.cliEnv()`.**\\n  The helper is a standalone function taking `(t, repoDir, remote)` but not the `TestEnv`. It constructs its own env with `testutil.GitIsolatedEnv()`, which lacks `ENTIRE_TEST_CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR`, `ENTIRE_TEST_GEMINI_PROJECT_DIR`, `ENTIRE_TEST_OPENCODE_PROJECT_DIR`, and `ENTIRE_TEST_TTY=0`. While the pre-push hook itself does not use agent project directories, the CLI's `PersistentPreRunE` calls `settings.IsSetUpAndEnabled(ctx)` which reads the `.entire/settings.json` in the CWD -- so this likely works. However, the pattern diverges from every other CLI invocation in the test suite (e.g., `GitCommitWithShadowHooks`, `RunCLI`) which all pass through `env.cliEnv()`. If any future change adds session resolution logic to the pre-push path, this will silently break. **Recommended fix**: Make `runPrePushInDir` a method on `TestEnv` (e.g., `env.RunPrePush(remote)`) that uses `env.cliEnv()`, consistent with the rest of the test infrastructure.\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:592-623] `TestGracefulDegradation_UnreachableRemotePushContinues` does NOT test what the requirements specify.**\\n  The requirements (P1 -- Graceful Degradation) say: \\\"configure checkpoint_remote pointing to non-existent path -> session + condense -> PrePush. Assert: no error returned, trails still pushed to origin, warning logged.\\\" The actual test sets up a normal bare remote, pushes to origin normally, and asserts no error. It does not configure a `checkpoint_remote` at all, so it is testing the happy path again, not graceful degradation of an unreachable checkpoint remote. This is essentially a duplicate of `TestPrePush_PushesCheckpointBranchToOrigin` with fewer assertions.\\n  **Recommended fix**: Configure `checkpoint_remote` pointing to a non-existent path (e.g., `/tmp/nonexistent-repo-XXXXX`), then assert that (a) PrePush does not return an error, (b) trails still arrive on origin, and (c) checkpoints do NOT arrive on origin (since they were routed to the unreachable checkpoint remote). This is the actual graceful degradation scenario.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:77-120] `TestPrePush_PushesTrailsBranchWhenItExists` does not actually assert trails were pushed.**\\n  The test conditionally checks if the trails branch exists locally, and if not, logs \\\"trails branch not created locally (expected for some configurations)\\\" and passes. This means the test can silently pass without verifying trails were pushed. The requirements say \\\"verify `entire/trails/v1` arrives on bare remote.\\\" If the trail system does not create the branch in this configuration, the test should be restructured: either (a) set up conditions that guarantee trail creation, or (b) if trail creation is optional in this code path, document why and rename the test to reflect it only verifies \\\"push when present\\\" semantics.\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:196-244] `TestPrePush_PushDisabledSkipsCheckpoints` does not verify trails behavior.**\\n  The requirements for `push_sessions: false` say: \\\"no `entire/checkpoints/v1` on remote, `entire/trails/v1` IS on remote.\\\" The test only asserts checkpoints are absent. It does not verify that trails are still pushed. Since the `PrePush` function explicitly separates checkpoint and trails pushing (checkpoints gated by `pushDisabled`, trails always pushed), the test should verify both sides. **Recommended fix**: Add an assertion checking whether trails arrived on remote (same conditional pattern as the trails test, or better, ensure trails are created).\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:253-362] Clone-and-resume tests manually fetch via `fetchMetadataBranch` instead of testing the actual `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` code path.**\\n  The `fetchMetadataBranch` helper (line 649) does a raw `git fetch` with a hardcoded refspec. The actual production code in `checkpoint_remote.go:274` (`fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing`) has richer behavior: it checks if the branch already exists locally, handles errors gracefully, and only fetches when missing. By bypassing the real function, these tests verify that git fetch works (trivially true) rather than that the CLI's fetch-on-first-session logic works correctly. **Recommended fix**: Either (a) invoke the CLI command that triggers `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` (e.g., start a session in the clone which should trigger it via `resolvePushSettings`), or (b) explicitly acknowledge in the test comments that this is testing the \\\"data arrives via fetch\\\" property, not the `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` code path itself. The requirements say \\\"start new session in B (triggers `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing`)\\\" -- the tests should match.\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:506-586] `TestConcurrentPush_SecondPusherMergesAndRetries` does not verify merge commit structure.**\\n  The requirements say: \\\"B's local branch has merge commit with two parents.\\\" The test only asserts that both checkpoint summaries exist on the remote. It does not inspect the metadata branch's commit history to verify the merge occurred (e.g., checking that the tip commit on B's local `entire/checkpoints/v1` has two parents). This is important because the fetch+merge+retry logic in `doPushBranch` is the core behavior being tested. **Recommended fix**: After B's push, verify that B's local `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch tip has 2 parent commits.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n- **[testenv.go:1752-1778] `PatchSettings` does shallow merge, not deep merge.**\\n  The `PatchSettings` function does `settings[k] = v` for each key, which replaces entire top-level keys. If the test calls `PatchSettings(map[string]any{\\\"strategy_options\\\": map[string]any{\\\"push_sessions\\\": false}})` and the settings already had `strategy_options` with other keys, those are lost. This is acceptable for current usage but could be surprising later. Consider documenting this behavior or implementing deep merge for nested maps.\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:649-662] `fetchMetadataBranch` helper swallows errors silently.**\\n  The helper logs the error but does not fail the test. If the fetch fails (e.g., branch doesn't exist on remote because condensation/push didn't work), subsequent assertions will fail with confusing error messages about missing checkpoint data instead of the root cause (fetch failure). Consider using `t.Fatalf` on error, or at minimum `t.Errorf`, so the root cause is visible.\\n\\n- **[remote_operations_test.go:689-721] `listCheckpointsInDir` reimplements checkpoint listing logic.**\\n  This helper parses the metadata branch tree manually using `git ls-tree`. The production code has `ListCheckpoints()` in the strategy package. If the tree structure changes, this test helper and the production code could diverge. Consider calling the production `ListCheckpoints()` (or a thin wrapper) to ensure the test validates the same code path. Alternatively, document that this intentionally uses a separate implementation to avoid testing the code with itself.\\n\\n- **[testenv.go:1629-1670] `SetupBareRemote` / `SetupNamedBareRemote` -- consider checking for existing remote.**\\n  If a test calls `SetupBareRemote()` twice, the second call will fail on `git remote add origin` since origin already exists. The E2E helper might handle this. Consider adding a guard or documenting this is one-time-only.\\n\\n- **Reduce test boilerplate.** The session setup pattern (NewSession -> CreateTranscript -> SimulateUserPromptSubmit -> WriteFile -> GitAdd -> SimulateStop -> GitCommitWithShadowHooks) is repeated 8+ times verbatim. Consider extracting a helper like `env.CreateCheckpointedCommit(prompt, fileName, content)` that encapsulates this entire flow. This would make the tests shorter and the important parts (remote setup, assertions) more prominent.\\n\\n### Coverage Gaps vs Requirements\\n\\n**Missing P0 tests:**\\n\\n1. **\\\"checkpoint_remote routes checkpoints to separate remote\\\"** -- The most complex P0 test is entirely absent. The requirements call for two bare remotes where checkpoints go to a separate remote. The open question about how to make `resolvePushSettings` use local paths was never resolved. This is the key differentiation test for the checkpoint_remote feature.\\n\\n2. **\\\"fork detection skips checkpoint_remote, falls back to origin\\\"** -- Not implemented. The requirements specify testing that when the push remote owner differs from the checkpoint remote owner, checkpoints fall back to origin.\\n\\n**Missing P0 Clone-and-Resume tests:**\\n\\n3. **\\\"clone with checkpoint_remote fetches from checkpoint URL\\\"** -- Not implemented. The requirements specify testing fetch from a separate checkpoint remote on clone.\\n\\n**Missing P1 tests:**\\n\\n4. **\\\"concurrent push with disconnected metadata (empty-orphan recovery)\\\"** -- Not implemented. This tests the `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` path.\\n\\n5. **\\\"unreachable checkpoint remote -- fetch on clone is silent\\\"** -- Not implemented. The existing graceful degradation test is misimplemented (see Critical finding above).\\n\\n6. **\\\"fetch timeout does not block push\\\"** -- Not implemented, though requirements note this may be P2.\\n\\n**Missing P2 tests:**\\n\\n7. **\\\"PrePush with URL target (not remote name)\\\"** -- Not implemented.\\n8. **\\\"fetch is one-time -- second call is no-op\\\"** -- Not implemented.\\n9. **\\\"push after rebase (shadow branch migration + push)\\\"** -- Not implemented.\\n\\n**Open questions from requirements not resolved:**\\n\\n- The `checkpoint_remote` routing question (how to use local paths as checkpoint URL) was not addressed. This blocks 3 test scenarios (items 1, 2, 3 above).\\n- Whether to test `entire/trails/v1` content vs existence was not resolved (tests currently only check existence when they check at all).\\n- The `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` one-time behavior question was not resolved (tests bypass the function entirely).\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- Good use of `t.Parallel()` in all tests -- follows project conventions.\\n- Infrastructure helpers (`SetupBareRemote`, `CloneFrom`, `BranchExistsOnRemote`, `PatchSettings`, `GitPush`, `GitFetch`) are well-designed and reusable. They follow the existing TestEnv method pattern, handle symlink resolution on macOS, and configure git properly in clones.\\n- `CloneFrom` correctly resolves the current branch name and passes it to `git clone --branch`, handling the bare repo HEAD issue.\\n- Test names follow the existing convention: `Test<Feature>_<Behavior>`.\\n- The `listCheckpointsInDir` helper correctly parses the sharded checkpoint structure.\\n- Good use of `t.Logf` for checkpoint IDs to aid debugging.\\n- `getRemoteBranchHash` in the idempotency test is a solid approach to verify no-op behavior.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\nThe infrastructure helpers added to `testenv.go` are solid and well-implemented. The test file covers the P0 basic PrePush flow and clone-and-resume scenarios adequately for the happy path.\\n\\nHowever, there are two critical issues: (1) the graceful degradation test is not testing graceful degradation at all, and (2) the `runPrePushInDir` helper diverges from test conventions in a way that could mask future bugs. Beyond that, several important gaps exist: trails push assertions are missing or conditional, the clone tests bypass the production fetch code path, and the concurrent push test does not verify the merge commit structure.\\n\\nMost significantly, the entire `checkpoint_remote` routing test category (3 test scenarios from P0) is absent. The requirements identify this as a P0 feature but the open question about local path routing was never resolved. This is the biggest gap.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address:**\\n- Critical fixes: ~1 hour (fix graceful degradation test, refactor `runPrePushInDir`)\\n- Important fixes: ~2-3 hours (add trails assertions, verify merge structure, decide on fetch code path testing)\\n- Missing P0 checkpoint_remote tests: ~3-4 hours (requires resolving the open question first)\\n- Missing P1 tests: ~2-3 hours\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":154,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":87106,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":154,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ3EWRuaq4K5ysrCUyuzE\",\"uuid\":\"87a7d8e1-e4f5-453c-9556-c029cabc3a12\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"ad42406d319a2f681\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_014YQbwbnEHrv7nfqKb7iB4t\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Q7e5mJkRpfnDzwkosr8V98\",\"uuid\":\"6b0a6fbb-1b08-4bfe-b4fc-e3bbdf6f13b6\",\"times