hContinues` tests git push failure, not PrePush graceful degradation (review-01 Critical #2, still outstanding in review-02)** - FIXED via a two-part approach:\\n    21→\\n    22→  1. The integration test (lines 611-663) is now honestly scoped: it configures `checkpoint_remote` with an unreachable repo, runs `PrePush(\\\"origin\\\")`, and verifies that because origin is a local path, `resolvePushSettings` falls back to origin. The comments (lines 617-620) explicitly state this tests the \\\"resolvePushSettings fallback\\\" path, not the `doPushBranch` error-handling path.\\n    23→\\n    24→  2. The actual graceful degradation behavior (push to unreachable target returns nil) is now tested by two new unit tests in `push_common_test.go`:\\n    25→     - `TestDoPushBranch_UnreachableTarget_ReturnsNil` -- calls the real `doPushBranch` with a non-existent path, verifying it returns nil after trying push, then fetch+merge (both fail), then logging a warning.\\n    26→     - `TestPushBranchIfNeeded_UnreachableTarget_ReturnsNil` -- calls the real `pushBranchIfNeeded` end-to-end, verifying the complete production code path (open repo -> check branch exists -> check unpushed -> doPushBranch -> graceful failure).\\n    27→\\n    28→  This resolves the long-standing issue from review-01. The production graceful degradation code path (`doPushBranch` lines 87-91 in `push_common.go`) is now exercised by real tests calling real production functions.\\n    29→\\n    30→- [x] **Lint violations will block CI (19 issues: noctx, unparam, wrapcheck)** - FIXED. All `exec.Command` calls in the new code use `exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), ...)`. The `createCheckpointedCommit` helper no longer returns an unused `sessionID`. The `RunPrePushWithError` wraps errors with `fmt.Errorf`. The `PatchSettings` uses `0o600` permissions. The user confirms `mise run lint` passes with 0 issues.\\n    31→\\n    32→### Important Issues from review-02\\n    33→\\n    34→- [x] **Clone-and-resume tests use `FetchMetadataBranch` instead of `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing`** - DOCUMENTED (review-02 acknowledged this as a reasonable tradeoff). Comments at lines 400-405 explain the design decision: `fetchMetadataBranchIfMissing` requires CWD inside the repo (incompatible with `t.Parallel()`), and is tested directly in `checkpoint_remote_test.go`. The integration tests validate the \\\"data arrives and is usable\\\" property.\\n    35→\\n    36→### Suggestions from review-02\\n    37→\\n    38→- [x] **Trails assertion in `TestPrePush_PushDisabledSkipsCheckpoints` is still conditional** - FIXED. The test now uses `ensureTrailsBranchExists` (line 232) to guarantee the branch exists, then makes an unconditional assertion (lines 238-239).\\n    39→\\n    40→- [x] **`REDACTED` rename suggested** - DONE. The test was renamed from `TestPrePush_ForkDetectionFallsBackToOrigin` to `REDACTED` (line 307), which accurately describes what the integration test actually exercises. Excellent.\\n    41→\\n    42→- [x] **`createCheckpointedCommit` could return only `checkpointID`** - FIXED. The function signature (line 372) returns only `string` (the checkpoint ID), not a tuple. This also fixes the `unparam` lint issue.\\n    43→\\n    44→- [x] **`PatchSettings` writes with 0o644 permissions** - FIXED. Now uses `0o600` (line 1867 in testenv.go diff).\\n    45→\\n    46→- [ ] **`TestGracefulDegradation_UnreachableCheckpointRemoteOnCloneIsSilent` could assert more** - PARTIALLY ADDRESSED. The test (lines 666-722) now verifies that a local checkpoint branch is created after commit (line 719), which is stronger than before. It could still verify checkpoint data content, but this is minor.\\n    47→\\n    48→### Coverage Gaps from review-01 (status update)\\n    49→\\n    50→- [x] **\\\"checkpoint_remote routes checkpoints to separate remote\\\"** - Present, well-documented layered approach\\n    51→- [x] **\\\"fork detection skips checkpoint_remote, falls back to origin\\\"** - Present as