 so `wrapcheck` does not apply to `_test.go` files. But the raw `exec.CommandContext` output is lost on error -- only the exit code is in the returned error, while the git output is only logged via `t.Logf`. If this helper is ever used in a code path where the caller checks the error message (e.g., to distinguish non-fast-forward from auth failure), the git output would be missing. Consider including the output in the wrapped error: `return fmt.Errorf(\\\"git push failed: %s: %w\\\", output, err)`. Very low priority since this is test-only code.\\n    73→\\n    74→- **[remote_operations_test.go:259-305] `TestPrePush_CheckpointRemoteRoutesToSeparateRemote` uses `pushBranchToTarget` (raw git push) instead of `pushBranchIfNeeded`.** Now that `pushBranchIfNeeded` is proven to work with local bare repos (via `TestPushBranchIfNeeded_LocalBareRepo_PushesSuccessfully`), the integration test could call `pushBranchIfNeeded` directly from the test instead of the raw `pushBranchToTarget` helper. This would exercise one more layer of production code. However, `pushBranchIfNeeded` requires CWD to be in the repo (for `OpenRepository`), which conflicts with `t.Parallel()`. The current approach is acceptable.\\n    75→\\n    76→- **[remote_operations_test.go:870-901] `listCheckpointsInDir` silently returns nil on error.** If `git ls-tree` fails (e.g., the branch does not exist because push/condensation failed earlier), the function returns nil and the calling test will fail with \\\"should find checkpoints from original repo after clone\\\" instead of the root cause. Consider using `t.Fatalf` or `t.Errorf` when `git ls-tree` fails and the branch was expected to exist. The current `t.Logf` makes debugging harder. Low priority.\\n    77→\\n    78→### Praise\\n    79→\\n    80→- The layered testing strategy is well-executed. The new `push_common_test.go` unit tests fill the critical gap from review-01/02: they exercise the actual `doPushBranch` and `pushBranchIfNeeded` production functions with real git repos and non-existent targets, validating the graceful degradation path that was previously untested. This is exactly the right approach for code that cannot be integration-tested due to local path limitations.\\n    81→\\n    82→- Test documentation is excellent throughout. Every test that cannot exercise the full production path has clear comments explaining (a) what it does test, (b) why it cannot test the full path, and (c) where the full path is tested instead. This makes the test suite self-documenting and prevents future reviewers from re-raising the same concerns.\\n    83→\\n    84→- The `REDACTED` rename accurately describes the behavior being tested, which was a recurring source of confusion in prior reviews.\\n    85→\\n    86→- The `ensureTrailsBranchExists` helper cleanly solves the conditional trails assertion problem across multiple tests.\\n    87→\\n    88→- The `createCheckpointedCommit` helper significantly reduces boilerplate. Tests read much more clearly with the setup compressed into a single line, making the remote setup and assertions (the interesting parts) prominent.\\n    89→\\n    90→- All 14 integration tests run in parallel and pass in ~9.4 seconds. The 3 new unit tests in `push_common_test.go` add important coverage with minimal overhead.\\n    91→\\n    92→- Good test count progression across iterations: 7 (review-01) -> 13 (review-02) -> 14 integration + 3 unit = 17 total (review-03).\\n    93→\\n    94→## Summary\\n    95→\\n    96→**Verdict: APPROVE**\\n    97→\\n    98→This iteration resolves all outstanding issues from reviews 01 and 02. The most significant improvement is the addition of three unit tests in `push_common_test.go` that exercise the real `doPushBranch` and `pushBranchIfNeeded` production code with unreachable targets, finally closing the graceful degradation testing gap that was flagged as critical in review-01 and remained unresolved through review-02.\\n    99→\\n   100→The lint issues are re